<HEAD>Dukakis Keeps Strong Lead over Jackson in Washington Democratic
Caucuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> held a strong lead over <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state party officials released results Tuesday from last week's Democratic presidential precinct caucuses. With about 68 percent of the precincts reporting the results of last Tuesday's balloting, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had 45 percent, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 35 percent, and 14 percent were uncommitted. All the other candidates were well off the pace, with <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> a weak fourth at 4 percent, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> Jr. 2 percent and Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> 1 percent. The Democratic Party made no effort to collect results statewide on caucus night, gathering precinct returns slowly by mail instead. Republicans say it will be at least another week before county chairmen submit the names of <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> delegates elected in last week's precinct caucuses The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reported last week that, with 71 percent of the Republican precincts reporting, former television evangelist <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> led with 39 percent. Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> finished second with 26 percent and Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> got 24 percent.
