<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 CBS and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said they will broadcast half-hour news specials on <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> primary election returns tonight at 11:30 p.m. EST. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> planned no full-length election special but will devote the first six minutes of its `` Nightline'' program at 11:30 p.m. to election returns, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> said it will provide periodic reports and a half-hour program on election returns at 1 a.m. Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> also were broadcasting brief special reports on voting results. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> planned five-minute news briefs at 8:55 p.m. and 9:55 p.m. and its half-hour special at 11:30 p.m., with `` NBC Nightly News'' anchorman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON> as host, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Callaghan </PERSON>. CBS planned one prime-time news brief, with the time yet to be set, and an 11:30 p.m. special program, with `` CBS Evening News'' anchorman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rather </PERSON> as host, said <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Dees </PERSON>, spokeswoman for the network. <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> will air five - to seven-minute reports at every half hour from 8 p.m. to 10:30 p.m. and will devote its `` Inside Politics'' program at 1 a.m. to election returns, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Kitsie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bassett </PERSON>
