<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Cartoons     03-15 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Cartoons,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korean Cartoonists Inject A Little Political Humor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 What <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> <PERSON> Min-sop </PERSON> is doing now conceivably could have landed him in jail not so long ago. He's drawing cartoons that poke gentle fun at <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> political leaders And people are getting a laugh out of them, without worrying that something could happen to them as well. <PERSON> Shim </PERSON>'s cartoons seem tame by most standards. Politicians and political parties are parodied as rival baseball teams and the jibes are never too strong. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> says, it is a remarkable change. `` In the past it was a taboo to caricature the big political names in this country,'' he said. Ridiculing the president or making jokes about him, for example, were seen as anti-state acts. <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> and other cartoonists have been able to take advantage of recent political liberalization in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to start injecting a little laughter and ridicule into politics. The cartoonists contend that political caricature is healthy and Korean politics can benefit from it. `` Cartoons and caricatures will bring the political leaders closer to the people,'' <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> maintained. Political cartoons have proliferated in newspapers and magazines and command large, enthusiastic audiences eager for a regular flow of material ranging from traditional editorial cartoons to long stories. Literacy is very high in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> but people prize cartoons for their humor. Newspaper cartoons so far are low-key and ironic. Some recent ones showed caricatures of the main political parties chasing each other in an unending circle, to symbolize ineffectiveness. Another showed top leaders as squabbling babies. A favorite of cartoonists is to have bemused Koreans staring at politicians battling for power and asking what is happening to the country. `` It is refreshing to see the taboos broken about the myths surrounding the political bigwigs,'' said <PERSON> Han </PERSON> <PERSON> Kye-su </PERSON>, a political analyst who has followed the growth of political cartooning. Many cartoonists say they have always seen their work as a way of calling for reform and liberalization. `` Korean cartoonists have been struggling for political change for a long time,'' <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> said. Cartoons are a valuable teaching tool that can vividly explain the meaning of an issue as well as amuse readers, <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> added. `` The political cartoonist can present the issues in a more amusing, but understandable manner to the public.'' The newly installed President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, who pledged freedom of speech and expression after years of authoritarian rule, personally encouraged cartoonists to take up political subjects by saying he did not mind being caricatured. <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> and other cartoonists say their work is still very gentle and restrained for fear of angering authorities and losing what freedom they have. But they say they expect to make their humor more biting as time goes on and liberalization expands. Cartoonists are also restrained by fear of offending a politician's supporters, <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s factional politics stress loyalty and supporters tend to resent any joke at their leader's expense, he said. `` The reaction can be terrible from the supporters,'' <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> said. `` People should learn to accept both positive and negative.'' Anti-government students and dissident groups, which have long used cartoons in their political literature, also are making greater use of caricatures, but usually not in a humorous way. The cartoons distributed at anti-government rallies and meetings are biting and bitter. Government and mainline opposition politicians are depicted as vicious tyrants suppressing the people with tear gas and clubs. Some are more subtle, depicting the divided opposition leaders as crying infants quarreling over a toy. `` They are not jokes,'' said one dissident. `` They show the people the reality of the government and why there is no democracy in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.'' Anti-government cartoons are distributed in pamphlets on college campuses or posted on trees and sidewalks at anti-government rallies. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, represented by a fiendish-looking Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> or a swaggering and bullying <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldier, is a fixture in the underground cartoons. Dissidents claim the country's successive authoritarian governments have survived because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> backing. One recent cartoon showed a tough-looking Statue of Liberty with a boxing glove on her upraised hand. <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> and other cartoonists reject their underground competition and the radical politics behind it. They say change must be moderate. `` It's too early to expose politicians to a more revealing fashion,'' <PERSON> Shim </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
