<FIRST>r i PM-Colombia-Elections     03-15 0777</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Elections,0806</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rich Still Run Colombia, But Left Makes Tiny Inroads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mayoral elections in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> have left a small crack in the political fortress of the upper class, the power behind this Latin American country since it won independence from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1819. The elections on Sunday marked the first time that mayors had been elected in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Previously, they were appointed by governors, who were appointed by the president. And the president always came from the <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> or the Conservative parties that are manipulated by the rich. But a leftist coalition, the <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION>, won at least 14 of l ,008 mayoral posts in Sunday's election, which in some cases brought people from the poorer classes closer to the seat of power in local politics The money and power of the traditional parties ruled out in most cases, such as in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, the son of former president <PERSON> Misael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pastrana </PERSON>, was elected mayor on the Conservative ticket. The <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> President </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virgilio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barco </ORGANIZATION> won 430 of the mayoral races, and the Conservative party won 402 mayoral posts. Coalition candidates won 24 of the mayoral elections. Other results may not be known for a week because of the remoteness of many towns. The showing by the new Patriotic Union was small. But the results were surprising given that the party was organized just three years ago. The leftist coalition also had to survive a wave of assassinations by right-wing death squads that killed 520 of the members of the party, including its president, <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardo </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> also had to confront a colonial attitude of patronage. Entire towns and areas traditionally adhere to one of the two traditional parties. Until recently, people did not join political parties. They were born into them. It is common knowledge that failure of a peasant to support the party controlling an area means virtual economic suicide. A loan application at the local bank for buying seed will be rejected. A worker will be turned away when looking for a job at a big hacienda. Colombians still call the rich <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosca </PERSON>, a kind of intertwined pastry. The term refers to a loose intertwining of influential people _ politicians, businessmen, landowners, doctors and lawyers _ who control the lives of the poor. Nowhere are the poor more aware of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rosca </LOCATION> than in small towns, where the wealthy own most of the rural land. A 1970 government study showed that 4.3 percent of the people in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> owned 68 percent of the land. Ten percent of the farms held 80 percent of total farmland. Those figures probably have not changed much. The government's concession to hold mayoral elections is an indication that <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> may be heading toward true democracy. The country has a long history of violence, perpetuated largely by a political elite that refused to reform partisan traditions. For example, elements of the Liberal party resisted social changes in 1948. A charasmatic Liberal leader, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Elicer </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaitan </PERSON>, broke away from the party and ran as an independent. <PERSON> Gaitan </PERSON> was assassinated shortly afterward. People saw their only hope of bettering their lives cut down, and the frustration exploded into the worst disturbances ever seen in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. That period, known simply as The Violence, has had an impact upon Colombian politics ever since. So when former president <PERSON> Belisario </PERSON> <PERSON> Betancur </PERSON> offered peace talks to the country's leftist guerrillas in 1984, most people approved. Perhaps they recognized that the need for social changes were again putting pressure on the system. The guerrillas said in 1985 they wanted a government more responsive to the poor people. For starters, they said they wanted the election of mayors. <PERSON> Betancur </PERSON> agreed, and the congress approved a constitutional amendement to allow the first election in 1988. The peace talks collapsed last year, but the government went ahead with the elections. The army says there are about 5,000 leftist guerrillas in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. The rebels claim they have close to 20,000 combatants. Whatever the number, their forces are growing each year. Ten years ago the army said there were only about 2,500 guerrillas. The growth of guerrilla forces and the possibility of another upheaval probably will depend greatly on whether the wealthy will concede to such programs as land reform, housing programs and building more schools and hospitals in rural areas. The government's attitude toward social change continues to be cautious. The election of mayors is a beginning, but not a solution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Wells </PERSON> is bureau chief for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
