<FIRST>r a PM-SovietEmigre     03-15 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet Emigre,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Svoiet Writer Finds New Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOONSOCKET, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet dissident whose pleas for an exit visa were ignored until he stepped up his reporting of human rights abuses has found a new home in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON>, 43, arrived in <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> last Tuesday after a journey that led from <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, a town in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Tolstoy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, an international, non-profit organization that helps resettle political refugees, found him an apartment and gave him enough money to live on for a month, said <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalpe </PERSON> of the Woonsocket chapter. <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON>, who had never been outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> before his expulsion, learned English by listening to British radio broadcasts and should have little trouble finding a job, Ms. <PERSON> Dalpe </PERSON> said. `` I will start with any job available,'' said <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON>, `` even washing dishes in a restaurant.'' <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> had been a dissident since the late 1970s, when he wrote what he calls his first `` open letter'' opposing the government _ a statement against the Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He sent the letter to the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Monitor and <ORGANIZATION> Helsinki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which published it outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` I did n't begin to hide until 1983,'' <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> said, because in general, it is safe to risk criticizing the Soviet government without reprisals for three years or so. But the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> patrols that began following him that year did not deter him. To make himself a difficult target, <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> began moving from city to city. He held odd jobs, and friends helped with money. Meanwhile, he continued to gather information about Soviet human rights violations, sending the information to groups interested in publishing it. Last fall, <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> found himself working as a theater decorator in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, a town whose former political boss, <PERSON> Boris </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON>, had been promoted to serve as the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s first secretary of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yeltsin </PERSON> was drummed out of office by party officials last November after delivering a speech that reportedly rankled powerful officials in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, including General Secretary <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Officials in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, however, took a dim view of one of their favorite sons being kicked out of office, and began demonstrating in public. <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> wrote about it. He sent his 3,000-word report on the demonstrations and a cover letter to <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, editor of a Moscow-based underground magazine called Glasnost. The sporadically-published magazine takes its cue from <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of `` openness'' in public affairs. But <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> never received the report. <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> assumes it was intercepted by Soviet police. A short while after sending it, he received an `` invitation'' to report to the emigration office to talk about his desire to leave the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` They say nothing until I was involved in the demonstrations,'' said <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON>. While Americans seem to be cautiously optimistic about the policy of glasnost, <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON> calls it a `` mask.'' He says Soviet society is intolerant of anything but the official line and there is no such thing as freedom of speech. `` I do n't like the socialist way of life in principle,'' said <PERSON> Kizelov </PERSON>. `` In my opinion, it is the wrong way of development.''
</TEXT>
