^By MOHAMMAD AFTAB</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pressure mounted Monday on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to sign an Afghan settlement aimed at securing the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops and end nine years of fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Sources close to the talks said the Pakistani chief representative, acting Foreign Minister <PERSON> Zain </PERSON> <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON>, received a message from the Kremlin calling upon him to sign the documents without further delay. The chief Afghan negotiator, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON>, scheduled a news conference for Tuesday, the day Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> named as a target date for the conclusion of the nearly 6-year-old talks. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will bring home its troops starting May 15 if the settlement is signed Tuesday. Both sides have said they do not consider March 15 a rigid deadline. Sources close to the talks, who declined to be identified, said that apart from pressing for the formation of an interim government, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> also felt that there are still some loose ends to be sorted out in the agreements that make up the peace package. The Soviet deputy foreign minister, <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> Loginov </PERSON>, told a news conference in <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, on Monday that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is still `` optimistic'' it can pull its troops out, but he acknowledged the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks are encountering difficulties. `` Nobody has set a definite deadline,'' he said. `` All that has been said is that if by the 15th -LRB- of March -RRB-, the last of the four agreements has been signed, then we will begin to withdraw our forces.'' <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has been insisting that the formation of a transitional government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> be linked to the settlement. Both <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> have adamantly rejected that condition. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> argues that only a broad-based government can guarantee implementation of the peace accords and the safe return of five million Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. `` We are ready to sign the moment our concerns are removed,'' <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> told reporters as his delegation left an afternoon meeting with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>. Before an earlier meeting in the morning, <PERSON> Noorani </PERSON> had said, without elaborating, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> would `` announce something today.'' But there was no such announcement as the talks were adjourned until Tuesday. In <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, where he was on a state visit, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was asked by a reporter if there was progress at the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks. With a smile, he said, `` There is,'' and `` There will be,'' but did not elaborate. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, president of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s pro-Soviet government, accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> Monday of using tricks to block the final agreement. `` It can be said candidly that that people who resort to ruses and who do n't want the document of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks to be signed are actually enemies of the refugees,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> was quoted as saying in an interview with the Afghan news agency <ORGANIZATION> Bakhtar </ORGANIZATION> excerpted by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, the official Soviet news agency. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> once said the only issue between the two countries was an acceptable timetable for Soviet withdrawal. He charged that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> raised questions about an interim