<HEAD>Israel Imposes Curfew On 600,000 Palestinians In Gaza Strip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> imposed a nightly curfew on more than 600,000 Arabs in the entire <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and reportedly sealed off entrances to the occupied territory after about 300 Arab policemen in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> said they would resign. The army on Monday also closed one of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s largest fruit and vegetable markets as <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> tightened economic sanctions in the occupied lands. Elsewhere in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers on Monday shot and wounded 11 Palestinians, hospital officials said. A 3-year-old girl was shot in the eye with a rubber bullet, and five Israelis were injured by stones thrown by Arabs. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said the 300 Arab policemen in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> announced Monday they would resign. They joined 450 officers in the occupied lands who turned in their badges earlier following orders of PLO-inspired underground leaflets. The curfew in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, announced Monday, was a reaction to the resignations, the radio said. The 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew also was designed to prevent `` the entrance of violent instigators ... and of written instigation material,'' it said. The army said the curfew was to prevent late night demonstrations. The curfew over the entire <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> was imposed for the first time since Arab unrest started on Dec. 8. It forces the residents to stay in their homes while entrances to <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> are sealed off by the army, the radio said. An army spokesman said the curfew would be imposed until further notice. At the <LOCATION> Erez </LOCATION> checkpoint at the entrance to <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Nash </PERSON> on Monday saw 15 to 20 Arab trucks and taxis prevented by the army from entering. He said soldiers would let in army vehicles and cars belonging to Jewish settlers who live in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>. Other Israelis and journalists were not permitted to drive in. `` Where would we sleep? We want to enter, all our families are inside,'' an Arab worker stopped at <ORGANIZATION> Erez </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. The situation in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>'s refugee camps was not immediately clear. On Sunday night, the army cut electricity and telephone lines to 41,000 people in the Beach Camp, an Arab reporter said. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities acknowledged that some policemen in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> quit but gave no figures. About 850 Arab policemen work in the occupied territories. The police control crime and direct traffic, but they are not used to quell <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> rioting in the occupied lands. `` It is clear their resignations were not handed in freely but because they fear for their lives,'' <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> police commander <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. Graffiti on the walls in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> called for the resignation of the Israeli-appointed mayor and city council, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said. In response to the PLO-backed unrest, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> stepped up economic sanctions. Shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> was banned as of Sunday, and a regional fruit and vegetable market was closed on Monday in <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION>, 20 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. Arab merchants said 70 trucks carrying produce were turned away Monday. In addition, the army ordered <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION> shop owners to close during the morning hours when <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leaflets said shops should be open. <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> said the Arab merchants responded with a total commercial strike. The economic test of wills continued on Monday in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where slogans painted in the red, green, white and black colors of the outlawed <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flag called for a two-day general strike starting today. Protests were reported on Monday in <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION> and the nearby <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Yamoun </LOCATION>, where troops using live ammunition shot and wounded 11 people, hospital officials said. According to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> figures, at least 91 Palestinians have been killed since anti-Israeli rioting began Dec. 8. Witnesses said Jewish settlers on Monday drove through the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION> and nearby <LOCATION> Al </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Amari </LOCATION> refugee camp, honking their horns. Witnesses said Palestinians then held a similar car demonstration, during which soldiers shot 3-year-old <PERSON> Rasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Yussef </PERSON> <PERSON> Said </PERSON> in the eye with a rubber bullet.
