<SECOND>PM-ATV Settlement,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>New ATV Settlement Stresses Advertising, Safety Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Advertising for all-terrain vehicles will begin stressing safety under a new agreement that also calls on makers of the off-road vehicles to set up new training programs and limit ATV sales. The government on Monday disclosed the new settlement, which could replace a preliminary agreement announced in December. The recreational vehicles have grown sharply in popularity in recent years, with more than 2 million currently believed to be in use. At the same time accidents have increased markedly, with more than 900 fatalities reported in the last five years, as well as 300,000 injuries, according to information collected by the Consumer Product <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. That led to a government safety investigation and the new agreement by the commission, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and the five manufacturers of the machines: <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Kawasaki </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Polaris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> will hold a hearing on the settlement April 18 and could order it into effect immediately. It would replace the preliminary agreement between the government and the manufacturers announced on Dec. 30. <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Terrence </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> said through a spokesman that the settlement is the biggest safety accomplishment in the history of his agency. Commission general counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said the settlement will continue the ban on sales of new three-wheeled ATVs and that manufacturers have agreed to buy back any of the three-wheel versions remaining in dealer inventories. The more stable four-wheel ATVs will still be sold, he said, but marketing of the full-size versions with engines of 90 cubic centimeters and over will be limited to riders aged 16 and over. Smaller machines will be allowed to be sold for riders ages 12 to 16, he said. The commission vote was 2-1, with <PERSON> Scanlon </PERSON> and commissioner <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> in favor and commissioner <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> dissenting. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, who also voted against the preliminary settlement in December, said in a statement that the settlement should have allowed <ORGANIZATION> ATV </ORGANIZATION> owners to obtain refunds. `` Without the refund, consumers are not obtaining the remedies necessary given the nature and severity of the hazards presented by ATVs,'' she said. The new 150-page settlement is much more detailed than the one announced in December, which drew criticism from <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and consumer groups as not being extensive enough. Some consumer groups have said all the vehicles should be recalled because of safety problems. <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said the settlement calls for the manufacturers to spend between $ 8.4 million and $ 8.6 million on advertising starting in the fall. The ads will stress the inherent safety risks of the vehicles, <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said, and will be placed in a variety of media. Included, he said, would be advertising on such broadcasts as the World Series, CBS Evening News and Monday Night Football. In addition the manufacturers have agreed to set up a national headquarters to develop safety and training programs for riders, and to provide hands-on training for all new purchasers and for all consumers who bought the machines since Dec. 30, 1986. Buyers will be offered incentives such as $ 50 in cash, a $ 100 savings bond or merchandise certificates to induce them to take the training programs, <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. Other provisions of the agreement, he said, include: _ New warning labels on the machines being sold, plus mailings providing these labels for all current owners for whom the manufacturers have addresses _ The hands-on training programs for new buyers will include their immediate families also _ Development of new owners manuals with added safety information _ Establishment of a safety hotline for consumers to get information and development of safety-related videos to be made available at dealer showrooms _ Elimination of the safety verification form that had been required as part of the earlier settlement This form, in which a buyer acknowledges knowing of the hazards of the machines, had been criticized by consumer groups, who said it could be used to protect the manufacturers in case of lawsuits stemming from accidents.
</TEXT>
