<HEAD>Revolt Shifts Gears: A New Emphasis on Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The confrontation in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> has increasingly become an economic test of wills between <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation authorities and Palestinians. Underground Palestinian leaders have persuaded many merchants and ordinary citizens to stop paying taxes and have enforced repeated strikes, keeping at home a large part of the 110,000 laborers who work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The measures are designed to make <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> bear more of the economic burden for occupation, which <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> activists say will give impetus to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s withdrawal. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has adopted increasingly tough economic sanctions, some of which are designed to put the squeeze on the Arab middle class. The army imposed an indefinite ban on trucks taking gasoline to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s 50 service stations. The move crippled public and private transport. <LOCATION> Qabatiyeh </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of several thousand people, was banned from exporting its quarried rock to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and visitors from abroad will not be allowed to visit the village, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials said. The move was punishment for the lynching of an alleged collaborator who was hung from an electricty pole after he fired into a crowd advancing on his home and fatally wounded a child. In <LOCATION> Jericho </LOCATION>, the army closed a regional produce market and ordered shops to close during morning hours, when <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leaflets said the shops should be open. `` The military government is trying to tell the people here who is boss. They want to hurt the people economically. I think they intend to try to break the strike this way,'' said <PERSON> Saeb </PERSON> <PERSON> Erakat </PERSON>, a political science professor at <ORGANIZATION> Al </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Najah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Israeli authorities have selectively used other measures as well, such as cutting off electricity to areas placed under curfew. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials say they hope such steps will encourage moderates to put pressure on Palestinian militants, although there is no sign that such measures are having the desired effect. `` Agitators on the Arab side want to disconnect the population as much as possible from any connection with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' said a senior official in the military administration of the occupied territories. He said the tax rebellion had minimal impact in January and February, leading to a 10 percent decline in revenues, or about $ 200,000 a month. But he said collections were expected to be far lower in March and that road repairs, garbage collection and other services in the occupied territories could suffer if there was not enough income to fund the $ 239 million budget of the army-run <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. To counter the tax boycott, authorities required Arabs to obtain a certificate saying they paid their taxes before getting import-export licenses, driver's permits and other documents. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> also lowered the amount of money Palestinians could bring from abroad without permission from $ 5,000 to $ 1,200. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said more economic sanctions were being considered to quell the revolt, which began Dec. 8. and has resulted in the death of more than 90 Arabs He declined to elaborate. But <PERSON> Arieh </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON>, former head of the army-run military government in 1974-76, said it might be necessary to stop Arabs from working in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> or using the bridges to trade with <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. `` Violence has peaked, in my opinion, but it will continue and it's doubtful whether it will stop without taking brutal -LRB- economic -RRB- measures,'' <PERSON> Shalev </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. <PERSON> Ephraim </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleiman </PERSON>, an economics professor at <ORGANIZATION> Hebrew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was better positioned to endure a showdown than the Palestinians. `` The occupied territories are dependent for income on three things: work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the export of agricultural goods and quarried stone to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, and financial support from Arab countries,'' he said in an interview. He said <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> job boycotts would deal a `` serious blow'' to the construction industry, textile factories, restaurants and garbage collection. But overall, he said, the `` economic impact on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is much smaller.'' Arab economists disputed the contention. `` We are prepared to suffer more than the Israelis,'' said <PERSON> Samir </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazboun </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Bir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> economist. He said the tax rebellion had added to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s cost of continuing the occupation and that bad publicity abroad had affected investment and tourism.
