<HEAD>Shamir Speaks For Half His Government in Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The following is a look at the main points of disagreement between <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace process. LAND FOR PEACE <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bloc </ORGANIZATION> opposes giving up any part of the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> in exchange for peace. Instead, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> calls for the implementation of the 1978 U.S.-mediated Camp David accords signed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. The agreement says Palestinians should be granted self-rule on domestic matters while leaving security and foreign affairs to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. After three years of autonomy, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the Arabs would negotiate a final status for the occupied lands. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> believes handing occupied territories back to the Arabs would endanger <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s existence by leaving it smaller and more vulnerable. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is ready to enter negotiations with <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, from which <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seized the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, which would involve returning parts of the occupied lands. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> says <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would insist on retaining <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> east <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> and holding on to areas along the <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> as a `` security border.'' His guiding principle is to hand back as much of the heavily populated Palestinian areas as possible, above all the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, taken from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> were occupied during the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. Today 1.5 million Palestinians live in the occupied territories along with 65,000 Jewish settlers. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> is afraid that if <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> keeps the territories, it will quickly lose its Jewish majority because of the high <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> birth rate. THE INTERNATIONAL PEACE CONFERENCE The international peace conference idea calls for negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> representatives under the aegis of the five permanent members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> _ the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> rejects the notion outright. He claims four of the five powers side with the Arabs and will have the power to force <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to give up the occupied lands. He believes the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will side with them on this issue. He also fears the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> will be invited to join the talks. As a concession to international involvement, he has suggested the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> invite <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> to talks, leaving them to negotiate on their own after a ceremonial meeting of the four delegations. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> believes <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> will negotiate only within an international forum and that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must accept this condition if it wants to talk peace. He says the conference will be only an `` opening'' of direct talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a joint <LOCATION> Jordanian-Palestinian </LOCATION> delegation. He argues the conference will not have the power to impose its will or interfere in direct negotiations and says the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> will not attend the talks. THE <PERSON> SHULTZ </PERSON> PLAN The peace initiative by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> is an attempt to bridge the gap among moderate Arabs, <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>. It calls for convening an international conference in April, followed by direct talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a joint Jordanian-Palestinian delegation on Palestinian self-rule. In December, even if autonomy negotiations were still going on, the sides would begin talks on a permanent settlement. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> says the <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plan is `` cumbersome ... and does nothing to guarantee the safety of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' His aides accuse the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of reneging on its commitment to the Camp David agreement. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> is against negotiating a permanent settlement while talks on the interim autonomy arrangements are still going on. He says the idea of autonomy was to see whether Israelis and Palestinians could live on a new footing before considering a permanent settlement. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> accepts the <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> plan, warning that it may be the last chance in the forseeble future to make peace with the Arabs. He says talks would be conducted while the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> government is in office. He describes the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration as the freindliest <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has ever known. THE PLO <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> both refuse to negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> has left open the possibility of talking to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> if it renounces violence and recognizes the Jewish state. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> will have nothing to do with the organization.
