<FIRST>r w PM-CapitolSecurity     03-15 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Capitol Security,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitol Police Gun Seizures up 147 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Capitol Police seized 1,162 weapons from visitors last year, a 147 percent increase over 1986, and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sergeant at arms is lobbying for $ 18.5 million to tighten security. Capitol police are responsible for the Capitol itself, six associated office buildings and the Capitol grounds. Sergeant at Arms <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> says the weapons confiscated last year included an Uzi machine gun, a pistol disguised as a beeper and soda bottles containing explosives. The 1,162 total compared to 470 weapons seized in 1986. The security plan advanced by <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> calls for installing bomb-proof glass in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> visitors' gallery and modifying floor seats in the chamber to protect against bomb blasts, at a cost of $ 4.2 million. Other proposals include a $ 4.7 million emergency telephone system to alert every <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> office immediately to a terrorist attack, $ 413,352 worth of additional bomb detectors in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> office buildings, a $ 3.5 million electronic card system for access to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> garages, and a $ 5.7 million alarm system connecting home-district offices with local police. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said most of the weapons were confiscated from visitors who were unaware of gun control restrictions at the Capitol and had no criminal intent. But of the total, 63 people were prosecuted, up from 50 the previous year. Strict anti-terrorist proposals, such as fencing in the Capitol grounds or putting glass enclosures around the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> visitors' galleries, have been widely criticized in the past. Many legislators argue that the Capitol, as a symbol of open democracy, should be easily accessible to the public. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> says this view is unrealistic in view of growing security threats. `` I think everybody _ me included _ would like the easy-going atmosphere of a Mayberry RFD police force, with a friendly cop directing traffic,'' he said in an interview. `` But in this day and time, you also need a high-tech, well-trained police department. You've got to have both.'' <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> outlined his plan last week at a House Appropriations subcommittee hearing on a proposed $ 1.96 billion budget for congressional operations during the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1. His next step is to seek spending authority from a separate <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee. Still awaiting final action by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leadership is a more sweeping security plan that calls for a wrought-iron fence around the Capitol Plaza, a parking ban on the plaza and gatehouses to screen visitors before they enter the Capitol grounds. That plan, scaled down from an earlier version, has been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, consisting of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sergeants at arms and Capitol Architect <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, but a $ 13 million appropriation to implement the plan remains largely unspent. Meanwhile, hydraulic steel street barricades have been installed at the main traffic entrances to the Capitol to halt unauthorized vehicles, and large concrete flower and shrubbery pots have been placed along driveways and sidewalks to thwart any attempted truck bombings of the Capitol. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said he hopes the bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leadership will meet with their sergeants at arms before the end of April to discuss the broader security plan. He said Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, has endorsed additional proposed security measures in the House.
