<HEAD>Legal Appeal Pressed, Protest Vigil Held</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 8-9 pvs bgng, `Meanwhile, the ...' to UPDATE with
Louisiana inmate put to death.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STARKE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> early Tuesday refused to halt the execution at dawn of convicted killer <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, who survived an unprecedented six death warrants and became an international cause celebre. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>, who has maintained his innocence in the 1973 slaying of a <LOCATION> Lakeland </LOCATION> businessman during a robbery, was scheduled to die in the electric chair at 7 a.m. at <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION> near this <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> town. The high court, in a 6-3 vote, denied a stay, as did a federal appeals court in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, a federal judge in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> earlier in the day `` I'm going to holler, I'm going to holler loud, and I'm not going to stop hollering, and I'll be hollering, ` Innocent, innocent, innocent' if they put me in the chair,'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said in an interview taped earlier Monday and shown on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Nightline.'' `` If I had committed such a crime, I would have a guilty conscience all these years. I could not have lived with it,'' he said. His case has become focus of an international campaign against capital punishment. Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> II and Soviet dissident <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON> had made appeals on his behalf. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>'s attorneys raised several claims on appeal, including reports of new evidence and arguments that the 54-year-old <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> had ineffective legal counsel. In <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, meanwhile, <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> was put to death in the electric chair early Tuesday for the 1978 slaying of a rookie policeman. The the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday had refused in a 7-2 vote to halt the execution. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> had claimed his wartime service in the <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War had made him insane, and pleaded with the jury to impose the death penalty to keep him from killing again. He later withdrew the request and fought his execution. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>'s appeals already had gone to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> four times. The last was rejected March 7 and Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>'s seventh death warrant the next day. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> on Monday dismissed suggestions he was rushing the execution. `` It's been 15 years,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. `` I think of the victim at a moment like this and the family which was destroyed. A hideous murder took place and that's what I keep in mind. Just because it's 15 years later, that does n't reduce a crime that was committed at the time. <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> was condemned for the shooting of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Turman </PERSON>, who interrupted a man robbing his wife, <PERSON> Helen </PERSON>, of $ 15. Mrs. <PERSON> Turman </PERSON> later identified <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> as the assailant. `` I think it was all very fair and <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> was the one who did it,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Turman </PERSON> told <LOCATION> Lakeland </LOCATION> radio station WONN. `` I was in the store alone with him for a long time before <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> came in and was shot. ... His face is still impressed in the back of my memory. I ca n't get it out.'' A neighbor, <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, also identified <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> during the trial. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing the shooting and Mrs. <PERSON> Turman </PERSON>'s cries and was shot three times. If executed, <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> will be the 18th man <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> has put to death since May 1979. Those men died after three or fewer warrants. Death penalty opponents claim <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> was railroaded because he is black, and that he is innocent of murder and has an alibi to prove it. They claim there is evidence _ statements from a minister and another person _ that <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> could not have committed the murder. The signing of the warrant last week gave defense attorneys only one week to prepare. `` A lot of people feel the primary reason for the seven-day warrant was to limit <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>'s ability to have sufficient time to mobilize a public opinion assault as they did very effectively for the sixth warrant,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spalding </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> Collateral Representative, a state-funded office of defense attorneys for death row inmates. Several hundred phone calls and telegrams had been received at the governor's office in <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION>, most in favor of clemency. The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on the Poor held a vigil in the Capitol rotunda Monday to press for clemency. In <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, about a dozen people demonstrated Monday outside the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>, urging <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to commute <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>'s death sentence. The protest was sponsored by the Swedish chapter of <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, which charged in a statement that `` death sentences in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are handed down with a great deal of discrimination and with a racial slant.'' `` Since January, I have received close to 2,000 letters from around the world,'' <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> said in an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published Sunday in which he maintained his innocence.
