<HEAD>Israeli Peace Activists Say Americans Should Speak Up Against
Occupation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prominent Israeli peace activists say American Jews who refuse to criticize the occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> are hurting <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. By remaining silent, the activists said, many American Jews have signaled endorsement of the policies of Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, thereby increasing the credibility of his views. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> arrived here Monday for talks with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. The peace activists planned a prayer vigil outside the White House when <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> meets with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Wednesday. But the activists said the Americans Jews opposed to <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> should make their views known. Those expressions could help curb the `` terrifying phenomenon'' in which <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> voters are moving to the right, said <PERSON> Yael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayan </PERSON>, daughter of the late <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dayan </PERSON>. `` On the whole, American Jews are not behind <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s policy,'' said <PERSON> Mordechai </PERSON> <PERSON> Bar-On </PERSON>, a founder of the Israeli group, Peace Now. `` They must speak out now.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, is reluctant to cede to the Palestinians land in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, two areas seized by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in the Six-Day War of 1967. His views are opposed by many <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, who favor a more conciliatory approach towards the Palestinians. <PERSON> Giora </PERSON> <PERSON> Furman </PERSON>, former deputy comm