<HEAD>Shultz Disputes Helms Allegation Of Misrepresentations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says that seven weeks of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> testimony have produced nothing to bar the speedy ratification of the new arms reduction treaty with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> angrily dismissed an allegation by Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, that the administration's public defense of the pact is based on `` misrepresentation'' and is at odds with facts presented in closed-door secret sessions. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should firmly discard all proposed amendments or reservations to the treaty, including one that would tie its implementation to reversing Soviet superiority in conventional arms in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He ticked off objections that have been mounted to the terms of the pact, which bans medium-range nuclear missiles, and asserted that all those objections have been refuted. The secretary of state, whose testimony opened the committee's examination of the treaty in January, commented as he made a return appearance to offer a summing up Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy majority leader and a respected vote counter, predicted that the pact will be ratified by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by a margin far greater than the required two-thirds majority <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will act well in advance of a planned <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> summit meeting this spring between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` We believe the treaty stands on its merits,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. `` It is self-contained and should not be made a vehicle for statements on other issues,'' including the Soviet military occupation of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. But he bristled after hearing <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> declare that there is `` a wide gap between the administration's public representations about the treaty and the information which we have received in closed session.'' `` Indeed,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said, `` after many hours of listening to testimony both private and public, the administration's public presentation of the treaty has been a tissue of confusion, misstatements and _ and I use the word advisedly _ even misrepresentations.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>: `` In a sense I do n't know what I'm doing here. Are you sitting here accusing me of deliberately misrepresenting? ... I can handle it fine when people say they do n't agree with me, but when they say I have misrepresented, I have trouble with that.'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> said he was not accusing <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> of `` deliberately'' misrepresenting, but he added that `` the contradictions are self-apparent.'' Replying to questions, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told Sen. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.D. </LOCATION>, that <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage of an amendment delaying implementation of the treaty until the West achieved a balance with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in conventional arms would kill the pact. The pact, formally termed the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces or INF treaty, calls for the destruction of all nuclear missiles with a range of between 300 miles and 3,400 miles. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he does not believe the treaty will cause <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to demand the removal of all nuclear weapons from its soil _ a step that some fear could open <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to intimidation by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which is said to have superiority in conventional, non-nuclear forces.
