<SECOND>PM-Trade,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Erase Gephardt Trade Plan, Senators Urge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators are starting to push their House counterparts in earnest to erase the trade plan that serves as the centerpiece of Democrat <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s race for the presidential nomination. `` We decided to stick with our own Super 301 plan and to oppose the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment,'' Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said Monday after a meeting of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees on the trade issue. As part of the action, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will ask the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to drop the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> plan from the final version of sweeping trade legislation passed by both houses last year. The decision was made by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> members of a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conference committee seeking a compromise version of the rival 1,000-page trade bills. It came on a voice vote in a closed-door session of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees. The move represents step one in a compromise process involving proposals that go back and forth between the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> until both chambers agree on one version. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s action represented `` nothing new'' in the trade debate. `` It's merely an opening bargaining position,'' he said. `` We're confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new, forceful legislation to open foreign markets And clearly the <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> amendment paved the way.'' <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s plan calls for negotiations to reduce <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s and other nations' `` excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. If those talks failed, the plan would prescribe presidential action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year. Such action could include tariffs or import quotas on Japanese goods brought into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The president could, however, take no action if there are considerations of `` national economic security'' or if the other country had a serious international debt problem. <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s amendment has been the chief basis of his appeal to blue-collar workers and others concerned over the impact on American jobs of products imported from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and newly industrialized nations in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. The `` Super 301'' provision that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is pushing would require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign trade practices listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative. It is named for the section of the Trade Act that deals with retaliatory steps against such unfair practices. Before sending their offer to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the senators planned to return to the table today and fashion additional provisions involving steps to combat `` dumping,'' or selling foreign-made products in world markets at prices lower than those in home markets. The senators also intend to work on provisions involving `` countervailing duties,'' or tariffs that are imposed to offset the price advantage that some foreign-made products get from export subsidies in their home countries. On Monday, the senators moved to expand from seven months to 12 months the time for the president to make a determination as to whether a foreign trade practice should be considered unfair.
