<HEAD>Biden Doctors Discuss Treatment Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s doctors are discussing treatment to prevent more blood clots like the one just discovered in one of the senator's lungs. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Esker </PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday that the clot in the lung was dissolving, but treatment would likely be needed to prevent further clots. Doctors could use anti-coagulant drugs or a surgical procedure, <PERSON> Esker </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, 45, was admitted to the hospital Sunday. He underwent an operation at <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> on Feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm _ the ballooning of an artery wall _ in an artery supplying blood to the brain. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> was recovering at home from that operation and waiting for an operation on a second aneurysm when he had to re-enter the hospital. `` Medical tests show that the senator did experience a pulmonary embolism, or a blood clot, that lodged in one of his lungs,'' <PERSON> Esker </PERSON> said. `` The clot, which could have resulted from decreased activity following major surgery, did no damage. Medical tests are continuing to determine the method of lessening the chances of other clots developing,'' he said. <PERSON> Esker </PERSON> said the alternative to anti-coagulant drugs is to insert a venous filter, a form of catheter, in a vein.
