<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Snarled Subway Snares Slow Senators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, struggling to make legislating a more orderly affair, put itself on a new work schedule this year and tightened up its procedures. The change produced unintended consequences. Under the new schedule the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> works in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for three straight weeks, then permits senators to return to their home states for a full week to attend to their constituents. The purpose of the change was to disband the so-called Tuesday-Thursday club, named for the age-old practice of many senators who left <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Thursday evenings and did not return until the following Tuesdays. Now when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> is meeting senators are expected to attend, Monday through Friday, no exceptions. There have been other changes as well. Roll call votes, which often were prolonged for an hour or more while the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> waited for an absent member to arrive from the airport or from a meeting across town, were limited to a strict 15 minutes each, no exceptions. And that caused the problem. The three <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> office buildings are linked to the Capitol by an underground subway. For years that subway has routinely and efficiently served two of those buildings _ the <PERSON> Russell </PERSON> and the Dirksen. But the tunnel which was extended to the new <ORGANIZATION> Hart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Building </ORGANIZATION> is far longer, as is the trip to the Capitol. And the Hart Building contains the offices of 50 of the 100 senators. Last month, seven or eight senators hurried to the <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> subway station with only minutes to spare to make a roll call. But the car was jammed with visitors. `` There were unusual circumstances,'' Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, D-Ala., told his colleagues `` There were some blind people on the subway car and it took some time to get them off.'' The 15-minute clock ticked to an end and <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> and his colleagues missed the vote. They demanded a solution to their transportation problem and a solution was provided. Tourists and other visitors were banned from the cars during roll call votes. And a subway car will now depart the <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> subway station precisely three minutes before the end of a 15-minute vote, giving senators just enough time to reach the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> chamber and cast their votes. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and its subway cars roll on.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>, R-Calif., was on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor earlier this month, holding forth with some heat on the turn of events that had seen <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> cut off all aid to the Contra rebels in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> `` Mr. <PERSON> Speaker </PERSON>, if I have told you once I have told you a hundred times that every time you cozy up to those communists down there in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> they are going to stick a rusty knife right in your back,'' he fumed, adding that he was off to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and would return `` with more facts and figures'' from a <ORGANIZATION> RAND </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> report on communist activity south of the border. He said he would seek permission to publish all of it in the Congressional Record. `` And I do not care if it costs thousands of dollars, and it will,'' <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> said in a shout. `` I want that whole report in the record, available to all the schools and libraries across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and everybody who follows the proceedings in this House through the written record and national technical means _ that means electronic.'' <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> stopped. Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, D-Wis., took the floor He had a question. `` I simply wanted to ask the gentleman from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> if any of us could help get him a sedative?'' Obey said. When the one-line comment appeared in the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Record </ORGANIZATION> it bore a five-word headline. The headline: `` A Sedative For A Member.''
