<HEAD>Removal Of Cardinal Seen As Political Manuever</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> was removed as mediator of the peace talks because he wanted the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> to discuss political reforms as well as a cease-fire with the Contras, sources said. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> diplomatically eased <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo from his job as mediator on March 2, thanking him for his efforts but saying the cardinal would not be needed for direct talks scheduled for next week. The manuever effectively removed the Roman Catholic prelate from pushing what were seen by the leftist Sandinista government as pro-Contra proposals. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has called for three days of face-to-face talks with the Contras beginning Monday in the Nicaraguan post at <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> on the border with <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said his brother, Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the nation's top military leader, would head the Sandinista delegation. The Contras countered by naming <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, their highest political leader, to head their delegation. Sandinista sources and opposition figures, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> ousted <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> because he outlined a proposal that would force the government to discuss internal politics with the rebels. The government has refused to discuss anything but a cease-fire. During the last round of talks on Feb. 18 in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> called on the Sandinista government to grant total amnesty, revise the military draft law, grant full press freedom and reopen stalled talks with internal opposition parties. He also suggested a 30-day truce. The Contras quickly accepted the proposal. The Sandinistas hesitated. <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON>, saying the two sides were at an impasse, broke off the talks the following day. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> on Feb. 23 sent the cardinal an angry letter, decrying the talks' `` abrupt suspension without consulation.'' The letter was the first in a week of exchanges between the government and the Catholic leader. The letters also sent signals that church-state relations had once again deteriorated in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. The strong <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> backed the 1979 revolution that ousted dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> and supported the Sandinistas. But the church later became the staunchest government critic and suffered repression. Since the signing of a regional peace plan in August by five Central American presidents including <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the situation seemed to be improving. The government allowed two exiled priests to return, permitted the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> station to reopen and in November asked the cardinal to be mediator. The cardinal's last letter to <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> was sent March 2, hours before <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> removed him as mediator. In it, the prelate reiterated the need for talks to `` put an end to the grueling war that daily claims 50 or 60 young Nicaraguans'' and said he was open to discussing a new outline for negotiations. A church source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> hoped to pressure <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> into backing out of his mediation role. When that failed, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> made his move and visited <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo that night. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> made it look like he was deferring to the cardinal's wishes `` The cardinal himself had suggested some time ago that a direct meeting -LRB- with the Contras -RRB- and in our country would be very important,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. For the past four years, <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> has urged direct talks. But the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> had repeatedly refused to sit down with the Contras until they were forced to do so by the regional peace plan. The plan signed by <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> calls for cease-fires, democratization, amnesties and an end to tactical or logistical support for insurgencies. The Sandinistas say peace talks should be held with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government because it financed and trained the rebels. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration refuses. During the first few rounds of talks aimed at working out a cease-fire, the cardinal acted as a go-between in indirect negotiations. In January, <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> proposed direct talks but with a mediator. After <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> was asked to step down as mediator, the Contras demanded he be involved in the meetings `` as witness, moderator and guarantor of the talks.'' The president responded on March 7 by calling on the cardinal to act as a witness, a role he accepted and which satisfied the rebels. The first direct talks in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> were scheduled for last week, March 9-11, but were canceled at the last minute by <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> after the Contras backed out and pressed for a preliminary meeting. The Contras later dropped that demand. More than 40,000 people have been killed since November 1981, when the Contras began fighting the Sandinista government.
