<HEAD>Carlucci Has Doubts About New Soviet Defense Posture</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE SHANNON</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs, Carlucci reaches Bern. Picks up 5th graf
pvs ``Carlucci was...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> wants his Soviet counterpart to cut production of tanks, artillery and heavy missiles to prove he is seriously pursuing a new defensive military doctrine. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, speaking to reporters today en route to a meeting in <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION> with Soviet counterpart <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, said that despite the extensive publicity surrounding the emerging <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> doctrine of `` reasonable sufficiency,'' he has seen `` absolutely no practical change.'' `` If anything, their military continues to grow. They continue to modernize,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> told reporters aboard his <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> jet. The plane refueled in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and then completed the flight to <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> was to attend a dinner with <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> tonight, and sit down Wednesday and Thursday for the first ever business session between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet defense secretaries. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> and other Soviet officials have said they are moving toward a new doctrine with a defensive posture. But they have never acknowledged that their past doctrine embodied an offensive posture, and various Soviet commentators have offered different views on the meaning of `` reasonable sufficiency.'' `` That's a question, by the way, I intend to ask him,'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` I'm still not sure what it is.'' If <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> wants to demonstrate that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is moving from an offensive to a defensive doctrine, the Soviets should slack off in tank and artillery production and `` maybe'' desist from the SS-18 intercontinental ballistic missile that carries 10 nuclear warheads, said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` One of the most important indicators, I would think, would be tanks. But tanks continue to pour out,'' he said. `` So there is no indication at the other end of the pipeline that there has been any change.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> side also wants to discuss so-called `` dangerous incidents'' such as a collision involving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet warships off the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Black </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> coast last month, and the fatal shooting by a Soviet soldier of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Maj. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON> on March 24, 1985, in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` One idea I have is for them to apologize for Maj. <PERSON> Nicholson </PERSON>, which they still have n't done,'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration wants the Soviets to agree on broad guidelines to curtail such incidents. The Soviets last month rammed two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships as they passed through Soviet territorial waters in an exercise designed to assert the `` right of innocent passage'' from international waters on one side of the Crimean peninsula to the other. On a personal level, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he was `` looking forward'' to meeting <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>. The meeting, the first of its kind and perhaps the first in a series of high-level military consultations, `` is kind of an interesting idea,'' he said. `` He was ... mildly critical of ` glasnost' as applied to the military, which seems to be a bit at variance with the standard line,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, although generally supportive of the reform policies of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, has said the policy of glasnost, or greater openness, must be restricted in the armed forces. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, dwelling on the meaning of the emerging Soviet military doctrine, said that `` sufficiency is a word that has been around for a long time'' since the detente era of the 1970s. `` Sufficiency can mean anything you define it to be, as best I can tell,'' he said. `` The -LRB- Soviet -RRB- military is saying that sufficiency is sufficient to meet the threat ... and, ` Oh, by the way, you have to have sufficient offense so that if the other fellow attacks you, you can attack him all the way to the ocean.' `` That does n't sound to me like anything new. At the same time, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is saying that there is something new. `` Some -LRB- Soviet -RRB- academics are saying, ` Well, maybe this means we can rethink our military establishment and do the same thing with less.' So obviously there is some kind of debate going on.''
