<HEAD>Israel Bans Palestinian Travel Between Occupied Territories</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with one dead, five wounded in West Bank
clashes, ban on travel by Palestinians. NO PICKUP.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAX NASH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EREZ CHECKPOINT, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities today banned Palestinians from traveling between the occupied territories, and hundreds of people rioted after a nightly curfew on the 650,000 Arabs in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Hospital officials said troops shot dead one Arab and wounded five today during clashes on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. No injuries were reported in the rioting in the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, police spokesman <PERSON> Rafi </PERSON> <PERSON> Levy </PERSON> said seven of 90 Arab polie officers had quit. They were the first such resignations in the disputed Israeli capital. Their action came after 500 Arab police in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> heeded a call by underground <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists to turn in their badges. On the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, a general strike called for by the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> got under way with transportation halted and Arab-owned stores closed. The travel ban between the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> represented an effort by the Israeli army to stem the growing campaign against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation inspired by <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>. An official of the military's <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said the measure applied to traffic in both directions. He said exemptions would be issued for hardship cases. `` They are allowed to work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but they ca n't continue into <LOCATION> Judea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Samaria </LOCATION> or vice versa. They would be turned back at a checkpoint,'' said the official, using the biblical terms for the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. `` The policy is not to separate -LRB- the Palestinians -RRB-, but to make it more difficult for agitators to move and to help stop distribution of anti-Israeli pamphlets that cause incitement,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The ban was the most comprehensive travel restriction imposed since <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> seized the areas in the 1967 Middle East War. Under Israeli law, Palestinians are allowed into <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to work but must have police authorization to spend the night. The Israeli military also said it would to take punitive actions against foreign and local journalists it believed had filed false reports about incidents in the occupied territories. Army officers declined to elaborate, saying a statement would be released later. Officials at <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mukassad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said a 22-year-old Palestinian from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> village of <LOCATION> Ain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yabrud </LOCATION> was dead on arrival with a bullet wound to the jaw. The Arab-owned <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> identified the dead man as <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> <PERSON> Hweih </PERSON> and said he was shot during a demonstration in <PERSON> Deir </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarir </PERSON>, 9 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Ramallah </LOCATION>. Troops also shot and wounded four Palestinians in <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION>, 16 miles west of <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, officials at <LOCATION> Qalqilya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> said. The Press Service put the wounded at six and said two