<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> peace talks reached a Soviet-set target date today but the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator, citing difficult issues still to be resolved, said negotiations will continue. `` We are discussing very serious, difficult issues but we continue to negotiate and look for solutions,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said that if an agreement was reached by March 15, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s estimated 115,000 troops would start leaving <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by mid-May. Neither side in the negotiations, which resumed today, has said the deadline was a rigid one or that the Soviets would consider going back on their pledge to withdraw their troops if the deadline passed without an agreement. But in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> today, the Soviets said failure to meet the deadline will delay the start of a Soviet troop withdrawal. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> said there was only a `` slim'' chance the accords could be signed by the end of the day. He blamed the situation on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s insistence that a coalition government be formed in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> before the agreement was reached. He accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of `` procrastination'' in the negotiations in an attempt to arrange a post-war government to its liking. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has said it wants a transitional government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> before the Soviets begin their withdrawal to oversee the Soviet pullout and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million refugees from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> say <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> should decide the makeup of its future government after the settlement is signed. The current round of talks, now three weeks old, has completed all main elements of the settlement aimed at ending nine years of fighting. Those elements include the timetable and basic logistics of the pullout of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops, an issue that has eluded a solution for several years. Sources close to the talks, who declined to be identified, said on Monday the Pakistanis also have reservations about some minor points in the complex agreement package. The sources said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> received a new <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> message during the weekend, urging it to sign the settlement without delay. Unconfirmed reports quoted <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> as saying that a decision on whether it would sign would be announced Monday. But there was no official word by nightfall. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s Cabinet has held three meetings since Sunday, apparently to weigh its next step. Meanwhile, the fragile seven-party <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas failed to decide whether it would drop its demand to dominate a future Afghan government. A guerrilla leader said on Monday in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> again rejected direct talks with the Moslem rebels on the Afghan issue. The resistance is represented by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks but its position has not always been identical with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s. The guerrillas have started to form a government of their own which <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> considers too hard-line. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began sending troops to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 at the request of the pro-Moscow government. The Soviet troops and the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government's regular army of about 50,000 men are pitted against 200,000 Moslem rebels, supported by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.
