<HEAD>Train Stalls World's Longest Tunnel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Passengers spent longer than they bargained for today in the world's longest undersea tunnel, which opened to trains two days earlier. A power outage left them stranded for more than three hours 460 feet underground in the 37-mile-long Seikan Tunnel. The tunnel links <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest island, <LOCATION> Honshu </LOCATION>, with Hokkaido, the northernmost main island. It cuts two hours off a trip formerly made by ferry. It took 24 years to build at an estimated cost of $ 8.5 billion. Most of the 166 passengers were asleep when the outage halted their 11-coach express train, bound for <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Sapporo </LOCATION>, about 12 miles from the tunnel's south exit. A locomotive pulled the train from the tunnel, and it resumed its journey from the next station, at <LOCATION> Aomori </LOCATION>, 3 hours and 50 minutes behind schedule, a <ORGANIZATION> Hokkaido </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The cause of the power outage was under investigation, said the Hokkaido representative, who spoke on condition of anonymity. Six trains have been stopped by faulty fire detectors since the tunnel opened.
