<HEAD>10,000 March In Protest Through Budapest Streets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 10,000 protesters marched through the streets of this Communist capital today calling for democracy and freedom of the press. Dozens of police patrols passed by, but authorities made no attempt to hinder the unofficial protest, which came on the anniversary of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s aborted 1848 revolution against <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. Protesters carried signs that read `` We Want Democracy'' and `` We Want Freedom of the Press'' and chanted anti-government slogans. Groups of demonstrators whistled and applauded when police vehicles passed by, but authorities refused to act on what appeared to be attempts to provoke them. The protesters blocked traffic and attracted large groups of passers-by, some of whom joined the throng as it meandered through central <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. Dissident sources said four prominent activists were detained in advance of the unofficial protest. The sources earlier report three activists had been taken into custody. Communist party authorities, meanwhile, held an official rally to mark the anniversary on the steps of <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>'s national museum, where the 1848 revolution broke out. Communist party officials laid wreaths and made speeches calling for greater national unity and economic progress. Hungarian dissidents have marked the anniversay by staging unofficial rallies on March 15 since 1973, and have met with varying reactions from authorities. Last year, police allowed thousands of people to march through downtown <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, calling for democracy as part of one of the biggest unofficial protests here in years. But in 1986, police clashed with protesters on March 15, and broke up that year's unofficial demonstration. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has won a reputation as a relatively liberal Soviet bloc country, although far less dissent is tolerated than in Western countries. One dissident source identified three of the activists detained this morning as writer <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tamas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mlynar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gabor </PERSON> <PERSON> Demszky </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s biggest underground publisher. The source, who asked not to be named, said two other activists _ <PERSON> Ottilia </PERSON> <PERSON> Solt </PERSON> and writer <PERSON> Gyoergy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gado </PERSON> _ may also have been taken into custody. He said friends were unable to reach them early today. Sources speculated the activists were detained to warn dissidents away from the unofficial protest, and predicted they would be relased later today. Police have raided the homes of at least eight dissidents during the past two weeks, including <PERSON> Gado </PERSON>, <PERSON> Solt </PERSON> and <PERSON> Demszky </PERSON>, sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. During the police search, hundreds of copies of unofficial journals, political documents and books were confiscated, <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON> said.
