 Former <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staff member <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> appeared before a federal grand jury today in the criminal investigation of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and a proposed $ 1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> worked closely with longtime <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> friend <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> in the summer of 1985, when supporters of the pipeline were seeking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for the project. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> is the second <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> aide in two weeks to testify in the probe of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> being conducted by independent counsel <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>. Former <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> aide <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wigg </PERSON> testified earlier. In addition, two former aides in <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s office, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, testified last week before the grand jury to which <PERSON> McKay </PERSON>'s office is presenting evidence. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> was <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s chief of staff before leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> several months ago <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> worked on <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s staff in mid-1985. The probe of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> revolves around whether he may have violated the 1977 Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, which prohibits bribes by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies or their agents to foreign officials. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> wrote a memo to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> in September 1985 saying that a portion of up to $ 700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> says he does n't recall reading the portion of the memo relating to planned <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> payments. <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> had been hired by Swiss oilman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON> to assist in the project and <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> went to <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> on the matter in May 1985. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> referred him to then-National Security Adviser <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> McFarlane </PERSON>, who directed that <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> assist the project. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was seeking an insurance package for the pipeline in the event it was bombed by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Then-Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> gave assurances that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would not attack the line, but <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> wanted a financial package to back up that promise. The <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> aides assisted on a number of proposed packages, initially trying to promote a $ 400 million bank-backed package acceptable to the <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The government agency insures foreign investments by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> firms such as <ORGANIZATION> Bechtel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which was going to build the project. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> left the <ORGANIZATION> NSC </ORGANIZATION> and his place on the project was taken by <PERSON> Wigg </PERSON>, who worked with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> on alternative proposals. Those included pledging <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as a guarantee for the pipeline and seeking to put <OR