<HEAD>Panel Finds Little Evidence That Cabinet Status Would Improve VA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An independent study group said today it could find little evidence that elevating the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to a Cabinet-level department would help the agency do its job better. The group and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said changes in the way the VA is managed should be made whether or not the agency is granted cabinet status. In a report to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a panel of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said it was not making a recommendation for or against a Cabinet-level VA.. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON>, chairman of the academy's seven-member study group, said the panel did not take a vote on elevating the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to Cabinet status, but he said, `` We did agree on the report. `` We are not here to discuss the priority of meeting the needs ... of veterans,'' <PERSON> Fischer </PERSON> told the committee. `` We are discussing ... structure.'' The panel, which did the study in seven weeks, found `` little evidence that the prospects of fulfilling the vital mission of providing for the present and future needs of veterans would be materially improved by elevating the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> to a Cabinet department.'' The panel also said it does not believe the elevation to Cabinet-status `` would significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and benefits. `` The panel does recognize the potential political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> a department in the president's Cabinet,'' the report said. `` However, given the broad political support which already exists for the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> and its programs, the gain would be at the margin.'' Legislation to elevate the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> has been endorsed by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and was approved by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Nov. 17. There has been strong support in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for passage. Governmental Affairs Committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said at today's hearing: `` If the elevation of the VA to Cabinet-level status is accompanied by significant measures to improve the management and operation of the agency, as well as to ensure the fair treatment of all veterans seeking access to agency services and benefits, then the case for elevation becomes much stronger.'' <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> said improvements within the VA legislation `` should be the goal of this committee over the next few weeks.'' The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, chartered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, provides independent advice on the organization and operation of government at all levels.
