<HEAD>Deputies Seek `Hard Worker' Who Allegedly Buried Stolen Cars And
Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HESPERIA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man who spent months industriously burying stolen cars, trucks and other equipment in the back yard of his rural home was being sought today, officials said. The man, identified as <PERSON> Korey </PERSON> <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON>, jumped out a back window of his home when he was questioned by a deputy, sheriff's Detective <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON> was being sought for an alleged role in a car-stripping operation. By Monday afternoon officials had unearthed more than a dozen cars and trucks plus various equipment and car parts, officials said. They also discovered numerous buried 55-gallon drums containing motor oil, gasoline and transmission fluid. For months, residents living in the desert 65 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> had watched as <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON> buried the vehicles with a backhoe, <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. `` A neighbor told us he was hauling out a trailer load of engines every other day,'' <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. `` He was a busy, busy boy. It appears he was working 24 hours a day. ... He could go through two or three cars a day.'' <PERSON> Sylvestre </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON>, who lives in a home just east of the house, said he thought his neighbor was `` just a hard worker.'' `` He'd be at it day and night,'' <PERSON> Carrillo </PERSON> said. `` He was a pretty good mechanic, or so we thought.'' Someone finally called the sheriff after seeing <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON> bury an almost-new car over the weekend, and a deputy confronted <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON> on Sunday. After answering a couple of questions, <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON> excused himself to go to the bathroom. Instead, he climbed out a back bedroom window and fled, <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. Police found a stolen red Corvette in the garage and secured a search warrant, <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said. Three people inside the house at the time were booked for investigation of grand theft auto, a jail deputy in <LOCATION> Victorville </LOCATION>, 10 miles north of here, said. They were identified as <PERSON> Cragg </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON>, 27, of <LOCATION> Hesperia </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, 26 and <PERSON> Sheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> VanSanford </PERSON>, 28, both of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Bail was set at $ 200,000 each and the three were scheduled for arraignment Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Victorville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, the deputy said. On Monday, county detectives-turned-archaeologists returned to excavate the cache of stolen property. The car-stripping operation apparently started about five months ago, and <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON> said officialos had not idea how many vehicles they might eventually find. He said investigators expect to find even more buried cars in the surrounding desert. `` That's just a guess at this time,'' said <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>. `` Neighbors say he would haul the backhoe out into the desert to bury stuff.''
