<SECOND>BC-ILLINOIS At-A-Glance,</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, March 15 Candidates filed: <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Babbitt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> Pledged delegates :173 Super delegates: 15 TOTAL: 188 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 15 Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 15 and Saturday, May 7 <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> is a direct-election primary, meaning its 113 congressional district delegates to the Democratic National Convention are elected directly from the primary ballot <LOCATION> Ilinois </LOCATION> Democrats will be faced with a two-part ballot in the March 15 primary. The top part of the ballot will be a non-binding presidential `` beauty contest,'' and the second part will list the candidates for national convention delegate. The remainder of the state's pledged national convention delegates will be picked by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> committee on May 7. They will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the number of delegates from congressional districts pledged to the candidates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, March 15 Candidates filed: <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Haig </PERSON> Delegates: 92 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, March 15 and Thursday, June 16 Selection of delegates: Tuesday, March 15 and Thursday, June 16 <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> have the same kind of two-part presidential ballot as the Democrats. The top part of the ballot is a non-binding presidential `` beauty contest,'' while the second part lists the candidates for national convention delegate. The candidates for delegate can have the name of a presidential candidate printed next to their own name on the ballot. Eighty-two delegates will be elected directly from the ballot and will be apportioned among congressional districts, ranging from two to five delegates per district. The state's remaining 10 delegates will be elected at-large at the state convention June 16-18.
</TEXT>
