<HEAD>300 March in East Germany to Demand More Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEIPZIG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 300 protesters defied police orders and marched in a human chain to demand greater freedom from the communist government, witnesses said Tuesday. Police did not intervene except to order by loudspeaker that the demonstrators disperse, the witnesses said, speaking on condition of anonymity. The demonstration came Monday on the second day of the <ORGANIZATION> Leipzig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION>, which draws visitors from 100 nations. The protesters came out of a `` peace prayer'' in the <ORGANIZATION> Nicholas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in downtown <LOCATION> Leipzig </LOCATION>, marched about 500 yards to another church where they sang songs, and then walked back to where they began, said the witnesses. The protesters voluntarily left after about 40 minutes. They were among more than 1,000 people who attended the prayer service at the Lutheran church, according to the witnesses. Church officials speaking at the hour-long prayer service were applauded when they demanded greater freedom for East Germans and an end to legal actions against those who want to leave the country, the witnesses said. An unidentified church official was quoted as telling the congregation that the country needs laws in line with international conventions. Officials of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lutheran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> have become increasingly outspoken in favor of improved human rights conditions in the country. The witnesses also said government officials banned a Monday night rally where activists had planned to publicize the plight of East Germans who are denied the right to leave the country.
