<FIRST>r w AM-Cabinet-LevelVA     03-15 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cabinet-Level VA,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Say Changes Needed at VA, With or Without Cabinet-Level
Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Significant changes in the way the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is being managed should be made whether or not it is elevated to Cabinet status, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee was told Tuesday. A panel of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, an independent study group, and the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, did not make recommendations on whether the VA should become part of the president's cabinet. But in its reports to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the seven-member academy panel said it found `` little evidence'' in its study that Cabinet-level status would materially improve the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s mission of providing for the present and future needs of veterans. `` The panel does not believe that such an elevation would significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and benefits,'' the report said. The panel said it `` does recognize the potential political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> a department in the president's <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>. However, given the broad political support which already exists for the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> and its programs, the gain would be at the margin.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said signficant changes are needed in the way the VA is being managed, and that they should be made whether or not the agency is granted Cabinet status. `` To appropriately manage any large, decentralized organization, top management must have reliable information on each unit's output and the resources used to achieve the output,'' the office said. `` <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reports have documented situations in which top managers were unaware of inefficient or poor quality services because they lacked complete, reliable and accurate data and the incentives to use those data to improve service delivery.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> recommended that the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s deputy administrator, or the undersecretary if the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> is made a cabinet department, be given the responsibility for the agency's day-to-day management. The academy panel said it had seen reports of internal weaknesses in the VA. However, it concluded that a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department is not required to make necessary improvements, `` although the creation of more presidential appointments could improve the quality of veterans programs by attracting better managers.'' A Cabinet-level VA could possibly achieve more uniformity of broad, cross-cutting national policy goals, the panel conceded. However, it said, `` there are other mechanisms now in place or available which have been, and could be, used to accomplish these purposes whether or not the VA is elevated to be a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> department although Cabinet status might make the current mechanisms work more effectively.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has endorsed legislation to raise the VA to Cabinet status. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed a similar bill last Nov. 17. There also has been strong support in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> for passage of the legislation. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> is an independent agency created in 1930. It provides health, disability, pension and death benefits to veterans, as well as loans and educational programs.
