<SECOND>AM-Capitol Security,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Capitol Police Seized 1,162 Weapons Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Capitol Police, who have arrested visitors carrying an Uzi machine gun, a pistol disguised as a beeper and soda bottles containing explosives, are worried about a 147 percent surge in weapons seizures at the Capitol last year. The police confiscated 1,162 weapons from visitors entering the Capitol or six adjacent <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> office buildings in 1987, up from 470 weapons seizures the previous year, according to House Sergeant at Arms <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Russ </PERSON>. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> is citing these figures to lobby for an $ 18.5 million plan to tighten security on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> side of the Capitol, including bombproof glass around the visitors' gallery overlooking the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chamber. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said in an interview that most of the weapons last year were seized from visitors who were unaware of gun control restrictions at the Capitol and had no criminal intent. These included constituents carrying out-of-state gun permits that are invalid on the Capitol grounds. Of the 1,162 arrests on illegal weapons charges last year, he said, only 63 were prosecuted, compared with 50 arrests prosecuted in 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> security plan being pushed by <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> calls for spending $ 4.2 million to install shatterproof glass shields around the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> visitors' gallery and modify seats on the chamber floor to protect against bomb blasts. He also is requesting a $ 4.7 million emergency telephone system to alert every <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> office immediately to a terrorist attack, $ 413,352 worth of additional bomb detectors in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> office buildings, a $ 3.5 million electronic card system for access to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> garages, and a $ 5.7 million alarm system connecting home-district offices with local police. Strict anti-terrorist proposals, such as placing a wrought iron security fence around the Capitol grounds and glass enclosures around the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> galleries, have been widely criticized in the past. Many legislators argue that the Capitol, as a symbol of open democracy, should be easily accessible to the public. But <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> says this is unrealistic because of growing security threats. `` I think everybody _ me included _ would like the easy-going atmosphere of a Mayberry RFD police force, with a friendly cop directing traffic,'' <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said. `` But in this day and time, you also need a high-tech, well-trained police department. You've got to have both.'' <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> outlined his plan last week at a House Appropriations subcommittee hearing on the proposed $ 1.96 billion budget for congressional operations next year, and plans to seek spending authority from a separate <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee. Still awaiting action by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leadership is a more sweeping security plan that calls for fencing in the Capitol Plaza, a parking ban on the East Front plaza and gatehouses to screen visitors before they enter the Capitol grounds. Although only authorized vehicles are permitted to enter the Capitol grounds, pedestrians may enter unhindered and are not screened for illegal weapons until enter the Capitol building itself, or adjacent office buildings. The comprehensive security plan for the entire Capitol area has been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, consisting of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sergeants at arms, the <ORGANIZATION> Capitol </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> chief and the architect of the Capitol. A $ 13 million appropriation to implement the plan remains largely unspent, awaiting a final go-ahead from congressional leaders. <PERSON> Russ </PERSON> said he hopes the leaders will meet before the end of April to review the broader plan. Meanwhile, police are using hydraulically operated, steel street barricades to halt unauthorized vehicles at the two main traffic entrances to the Capitol grounds. In addition, large concrete flower and shrubbery pots stand along driveways and sidewalks to thwart any attempted truck bombings of the Capitol.
