<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> registered his objections today to a <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace conference and Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the two had been unable to bridge their differences on a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal for negotiations on settling the <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> conflict. But both pledged to continue their efforts. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, in a speech to an American Jewish audience, described the situation in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> as `` urgent.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also gave assurances in talking to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION> that `` we will not leave <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to stand alone, nor will we acquiesce in any effort to gang up on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' The president added: `` Peace will not be imposed by us or by anyone else. It will and must come from the genuine give-and-take of negotiations. That's what we're working to set in motion now.'' Emerging with <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> from a 90-minute session at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said `` we have n't found our way to bridge all of the differences.'' But, he said, `` I see quite clearly what the nature of the difference are and what they are n't.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> did not offer any details, but <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> underscored a major disagreement with the plan for negotiations <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> devised two weeks ago and proposed to Arab and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> leaders. `` We are interested, first of all, to negotiate directly with all the parties concerned,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said. `` We do n't see any positive role for an international conference.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s plan would have an international conference attended by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> convene last month and set the stage for negotiations between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and a mixed <LOCATION> Jordanian-Palestinian </LOCATION> delegation by May 1. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> is concerned the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which do not have relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, would try to tilt the outcome in the Arabs' favor. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> called his session with <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> `` very constructive and worthwhile'' and said `` we feel encouraged to continue our efforts to work with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and others in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> to seek greater stability, constructive and peaceful relations in the region.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said their talk was ` ` very serious and thorough. He pledged to cooperate with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and others in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government `` to get peace and to enhance the prospects for peace in our area.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, meanwhile, added <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, a television evangelist seeking the Repulbicn presidential nomination, to his afternoon schedule. In a tough speech Monday night to an American Jewish group, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said yielding territory on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> would invite another attempt by the Arabs to destroy <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` These matters are questions of life and death, of our very existence,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZ