<FIRST>u w PM-Ozone 2ndLd-Writethru a0475 03-15 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0475,680</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 6th graf pvs, ``At this, to CORRECT typo in Rowland's
name and spelling of ``Irvine.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The protective ozone layer over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> appears to have shrunk about 2.3 percent since 1969, scientists said today in the most thorough study yet of ozone depletion. Experts have estimated that a 1 percent depletion could mean a 5 percent to 6 percent increase in skin cancers. But today's report from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the work of more than 100 experts over 17 months, put the annual ozone depletion over the mid-latitudes of the northern hemisphere at a much higher rate. Those latitudes, 30 degrees to 64 degrees, take in all of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> except southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and extend halfway up <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s Yukon Territory. The scientists laid the responsibility for the ozone depletion squarely on chlorofluorocarbons -LRB- CFCs -RRB-, chemicals used to power some aerosol sprays. `` At this point there is no other culprit to blame,'' said <PERSON> Sherwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Irvine </LOCATION>. `` We have taken out all the natural phenomena that are believed to affect ozone.'' The report also said that the annual springtime depletion of ozone over <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> appears to be diluting ozone yearround over the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hemisphere </ORGANIZATION> to about 60 degrees southern latitude, a point midway between the tip of the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION> at the southern tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Rowland </PERSON>, who headed one <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> study groups, said the scientists had re-examined years of ground-based and satellite observations of the atmosphere to remove the normal biennial fluctuations of many atmospheric characteristics and also the effects of the 11-year solar cycle. The ground-based observations were limited to mid-latitudes in the Northern Hemisphere because there are few stations elsewhere in the world. But never before have scientists re-analyzed the monthly data at differing latitudes to try to remove the solar and biennial fluctuations. Ozone in the atmosphere 15 miles to 25 miles up filters out the sun's ultraviolet rays, making life on earth possible. The same ultraviolet breaks up the <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds, liberating chlorine, which in turn destroys ozone. Ozone is a pollutant on the ground, but CFCs do n't break up there _ not enough ultraviolet gets through. CFCs were banned as aerosol propellants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1978, and worldwide emissions declined. There was one report in 1983 from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> that said future ozone decline would be only 2 percent to 4 percent. But <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use started growing again, in part because one compound turned out to be ideal for cleaning computer chips and other electronic parts. Other major uses are for refrigeration fluids and as blowing agents in making plastic foams. Then an annual ozone `` hole'' over the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> was discovered, and records going back to 1958 showed that it had n't happened before the late 1970s. Discovery of the ozone hole _ an annual Antarctic springtime plunge in ozone concentrations, last year by a record 50 percent _ spurred treaty negotiators last fall in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has estimated that a 1 percent thinning of the Earth's ozone shield means a 5 percent to 6 percent increase in skin cancer. If <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> use continued increasing at 2.5 percent per year, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said, 20 percent of the ozone barrier could be gone in the next century. Today's report came one day after the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, on a vote of 83-0, became the first major chemical-producing nation to ratify a 31-country treaty cutting emissions that damage the Earth's protective ozone layer The treaty commits the signers to a 50 percent cut from 1986 levels in production of compounds called chlorofluorocarbons, CFCs, by 1998. The treaty will be officially ratified when the president signs it. Though the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be the first major producer of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds to ratify, it is not the first ratifier _ that is <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. Under the treaty, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says, the decline would slow to the point where it would be swamped by the normal year-to-year fluctuations. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has several <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> plants under construction, and won concessions permitting it to exceed the treaty limits for a time _ which led to a Soviet treaty signature in December. Similar provisions were made for developing countries. If those exceptions are used, the Environmental Defense Fund has estimated, the actual 1998 rollback in emissions could be 35 percent instead of 50 percent.
