<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House, pushing for new aid to the Nicaraguan rebels, told congressional leaders today the Sandinista regime appears to be preparing `` an all-out death blow'' against the Contras, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. Describing a lengthy meeting in which President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> discussed the possibility of a new Contra aid package with lawmakers, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> quoted national security adviser <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> as saying: `` The resistance program is on the verge of collapse. It's only a matter of weeks.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> `` asked for bipartisan support to keep the resistance from withering away and to prevent a dismantling of the infrastructure that supports the Contras.'' The spokesman said that in the Cabinet Room meeting, `` General <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> outlined the buildup of <LOCATION> Sandindista </LOCATION> forces for an offensive in the <LOCATION> Bocay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, and it was indicated that Sandinista forces appear to be preparing to launch an all-out death blow to the Contras by destroying the supplies now in major Contra camps.'' `` There was a considerable discussion of this turn of events.. and the implication that has for the peace process,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said But he stressed that no decisions were reached in the meeting about how to proceed with a humanitarian aid package. `` I think everyone in there agreed it was a time to look forward and to talk about how to fashion a new package, and let the fights and arguments in the past stay there,'' the spokesman said. `` There was no anger. ... Everyone, I think, was intense in the sense that they think this was a time of decision for the national government.'' `` I think it's important to point out that everyone in that session agreed a cease fire is what we're going after and that if you get a cease fire, that relieves the tension for lethal aid and for an awful lot of other kinds of aid,'' he said. `` The important thing now is the humanitarian package that we could use to meet their human needs.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, speaking to the Prime Ministers Club earlier, accused the Sandinistas of practicing religious oppression, particularly against Jews. He said President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s government had aligned itself with <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, talking to reporters following today's meeting <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, reiterated that he would be willing to reconsider a $ 30 million humanitarian aid package that was defeated 216-208 in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on March 3. `` We told the president that we had worked very diligently, Democrats and Republicans, to put together a package'' which was defeated, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said. `` We would be glad to run it again if they -LRB- the House Republicans -RRB- would be of a mind to vote for it.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said it would be virtually impossible to suspend <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> rules to get a vote on a new package this week, as the administration wants. And one congressional supporter of renewed Contra aid, Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., said an aid package he has been working on was `` on hold'' for the moment while aid backers look for a way to get agreement in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, always the most problematic hurdle on the Contra issue <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, appearing before the <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a group of approximately 150 supporters of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>, said that among other reasons the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should support the Contra rebels is the oppression of Jews in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. `` Few regimes today so blatantly sanction and practice official anti-Semitism as the Sandinista communists in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` The Jewish community has been forced out almost entirely. <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>'s one synagogue has been defaced and firebombed. ... `` `` <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> has officially aligned itself with <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gadhafi </PERSON>,'' he said, `` and, of course, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> _ an organization that has again revealed its true colors, opposing our efforts for peace and trumpeting its responsibility for a sickening terrorist attack on a bus carrying Israeli men, woman and children.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> `` have led the way in sponsoring anti-Israel resolutions in <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. So I think it's time that some in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who want to turn away from the reality of left-wing anti-Semitism face the facts about the anti-Semitism of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> as well as their ties to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and other terrorist groups.'' `` It is the Nicaraguan freedom fighters who are resisting this kind of moral corruption,'' he said. `` It is the freedom fighters who are fighting for the political, civil and human rights of Jews and Christians in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The rebels and the Sandinista government have agreed to sit down and talk about their 7