<HEAD>Planned Parenthood Honors Katharine Hepburn and Mother</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT that Hepburn was in film of
``Spitfire,'' not the Broadway show; Note language of 5th graf</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON> was starring in the 1934 film `` Spitfire,'' her mother was getting plenty of her own attention as a `` spitfire'' for her outspoken support of birth control for women. Today, the 79-year-old Miss <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON>, with her family's characteristic wit and keen intelligence, has taken on her mother's cause and become one of Planned Parenthood's staunchest In a tribute Monday night, entitled `` Celebrating Two Generations of Individual Courage,'' the actress and her late mother, <PERSON> Katharine </PERSON> <PERSON> Houghton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON>, were honored by Planned Parenthood for their efforts to gain greater reproductive rights for women. `` It's a frightfully important subject,'' the actress told the 1,100 guests gathered at the Waldorf-Astoria for the black-tie event. `` And I'm damn lucky to have had a mother who waked me up at an early age.'' Tickets for the gala were priced from $ 500 to $ 1,000, with proceeds going to Planned Parenthood dedicated to the actress' three priorities: keeping abortion safe and legal, preventing teen pregnancies and preserving family planning for the poor Former TV anchorman <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON>, tennis champion <PERSON> Martina </PERSON> <PERSON> Navratilova </PERSON>, TV journalist <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> and actor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON>, star of the Broadway musical `` Me and My Girl,'' were among the participants. As guests arrived, they encountered a small protest by the Stop Planned Parenthood organization. Guests rose to their feet and applauded as Miss <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON>, elegantly attired in a black pantsuit, approached the podium. `` It's so touching to me, I can hardly begin to say what I have to say,'' she said. But she had much to say. `` When a girl becomes pregnant, should she be forced by law to have this baby? She's 13. She does n't want it. She ca n't support it. Her family does n't want it. It would seem to me that she should be allowed to have an abortion.'' `` By the same token, if an older woman with several children gets pregnant and feels that she ca n't support it or care for another child, I can not for the life of me see that anyone but this woman has the right to decide what she's going to do,'' Miss <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON> said. `` It's certainly much harder to be a woman than it is to be a man,'' she lamented. `` But men got here first and arranged everything to suit themselves. And it's taking women a long time to ... try to catch up.'' Miss <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON> became involved with Planned Parenthood in 1981. The group's president, <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Wattleton </PERSON>, said she recruited her because she was `` someone who really had the public's respect.'' Her participation in the organization has brought an additional 200,000 donors and supporters. It was only after the actress agreed to work for Planned Parenthood that, Ms. <PERSON> Wattleton </PERSON> said, she learned `` serendipitously'' that Miss <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON>'s mother had been an outspoken advocate of birth control at a time when it was illegal. Mrs. <PERSON> Hepburn </PERSON> worked alongside Planned Parenthood founder <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanger </PERSON> more than 70 years ago. A member of the <PERSON> Houghton </PERSON> family that founded Corning Glass, she testified before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in the 1930s on the need for birth control, particularly for poor women. `` Women want children but they want children they can properly take care of,'' she testified. She died in 1951 at age 73.
