<HEAD>Students Given Taxing Task: Simplifying IRS Forms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Students at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Akron </ORGANIZATION> are aiming for a breakthrough that has eluded some of the best minds in government and the professions: a tax form that can be understood without a college education. `` We know it can be done and we're going to prove it,'' Professor <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Creme </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in the university's law school, said in an interview Tuesday. `` We're not saying we could bring it down to a second-grade level, but we certainly can make it simpler. `` If you simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile toward the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` And you'll raise a lot more revenue.'' <PERSON> Creme </PERSON> said about 20 students majoring in law, business or education will be put to work on the project. Testifying before a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Monday, some of the students and their leaders promised Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., that most of the work will be done by September The students got interested after seeing estimates that nine of 10 people with less than a high school education can not understand the instructions for the simplest tax form _ the one-page 1040EZ. That study also determined that it takes less reading skill to get through a typical issue of the Wall Street Journal than through a tax form. The reasons for the complexity are simple, say Creme and Professor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Childs </PERSON>, director of the university's Tax Clinic. `` The average sentence length of these -LRB- IRS -RRB- publications exceeds 25 words ... One-third of the words in these publications are multi-syllabled words.'' `` By reducing the number of syllables and the number of words in a sentence we can the forms and instructions significantly more readable,'' said <PERSON> Creme </PERSON>. `` And we want to change how the forms look _ change the spacing so things do n't look so crammed in.'' It is not just college students or even high school dropouts who are having trouble with tax forms. Even tax professionals shake their heads at some instructions that were prompted by some of the more complex provisions in the 1986 tax overhaul. This sentence, for example, is in the instructions for Form 8598, which up to 1 million taxpayers will have to file this year to calculate their mortgage-interest deduction: `` If you received monthly statements that show either the closing balance or the average balance for the month, you may determine your average balance by taking the average of either the closing balances or average monthly balances shown on your monthly statement.'' <PERSON> Creme </PERSON> said participants hope to develop more-readable versions of the W-4 withholding form; W-2 year-end wages-earned statement; 1099 interest-earned form and the basic 1040, 1040A and 1040EZ forms. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> forms are developed in consultation with lawyers, accountants and educators. In changing its forms last year to reflect the new tax law, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> hired a consultant and even went to some shopping malls for instant reaction from random taxpayers. <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyrek </PERSON>, who helped develop the 1040EZ several years ago, says that form is written to an eighth-grade reading level. That does not mean, however, that a typical student in the eighth grade could understand it, he said. `` It means a grownup that understands certain concepts can understand the form,'' <PERSON> Pyrek </PERSON> said. `` A fourth grader does n't understand the concept of taxation, for example, although a 40-year-old with a fourth-grade education who has been on the job for 20 years probably does. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> concedes that many taxpayers find taxes puzzling. The agency's own statistics show that 46 percent of taxpayers paid professionals to fill out their returns last year. Nevertheless, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> contends that the forms and instructions are about as simple as they can be to reflect a complicated tax law. <PERSON> Creme </PERSON>, a tax lawyer for 20 years, said the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has nothing to lose by making its forms more understandable. `` When people ca n't figure out the right answer,'' he said, `` they will take the answer that gives them the best break.
