 A lawyer planned an appeal and the government agreed Tuesday to hear more calls for clemency for the `` <ORGANIZATION> Sharpeville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Six </ORGANIZATION>,'' a group of blacks sentenced to hang in two days. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> joined the growing international call for mercy for the five men and one woman, who were convicted of complicity in the 1984 lynching of a black township official. `` I am not saying that a sign of mercy will solve the problems of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> but it might be a little signal that human feelings have not died out altogether,'' West German President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> told a news coference in <LOCATION> Harare </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, where he was on a state visit. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> has rejected all clemency bids for the six, the goverment said Tuesday. But he agreed to meet Thursday with two members of the anti-apartheid <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> who oppose the executions, the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported. Also, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that further petitions for mercy would be given `` careful consideration.'' <PERSON> Prakash </PERSON> <PERSON> Diar </PERSON>, attorney for the six, said he would file an appeal in the <ORGANIZATION> Rand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday to seek a stay of execution. British Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, meanwhile, said she asked <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATIO