who is only too willing to negotiate with us.'' <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said British Ambassador <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Renwick </PERSON> was given instructions `` to express my hope that President <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> will see fit, even at this late stage, to exercise the perogative of mercy.'' <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Weizsaecker </PERSON> told reporters that the executions would contribute to the violence and tension in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, where the system of apartheid gives control of the country to the white minority. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the London-based human rights organization, also urged <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> to spare the six. The organization expressed shock that 164 people, only nine of them white, were hanged in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> last year. <PERSON> Dlamini </PERSON>'s killing came during riots that sparked a two-year outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid unrest that left more than 2,000 blacks dead. Black activists frequently targeted black township councilors, considering them collaborators with the white-led government. The <LOCATION> Sharpeville </LOCATION> riots were provoked by the local council's decision to raise rents.
