<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Switch,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whites to Live in Black Township for Four Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 200 black and white Christians will live and worship together this week in an unusual attempt to break down the psychological and social barriers created by apartheid. Most of the participants are whites coming from across <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to stay Wednesday night through Sunday in <LOCATION> Mamelodi </LOCATION>, the main black township outside <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION>. About 35 blacks from <ORGANIZATION> Mamelodi </ORGANIZATION> will stay in white homes in the capital. The encounter, culminating with a community barbecue and and a church service, will be the largest interracial get-together of its type in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. One of the principal organizers is the Rev. <PERSON> Nico </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a Dutch Reformed minister in <LOCATION> Mamelodi </LOCATION> since 1982. He moved there two years ago after becoming the first white permitted by the government to live in a black township. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> says relations between the races in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> are warped by fear and estrangement. `` Since I'm living in the black community myself, I have become aware of the almost total alienation which has developed between whites and blacks,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` Apartheid was successful. It brought about what it promised to do. It separated people,'' he said. `` If people are forced to live separately they become strangers ... Eventually on both sides they have certain perceptions are totally different from the real people. This eventually turns into fear of one another.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and other clergymen organizing the four days of socializing, Bible study and prayer have brought smaller groups of whites into <LOCATION> Mamelodi </LOCATION> in the past. They said men and women sometimes tremble with fear as they enter a township that two years ago was wracked by violent anti-apartheid protests, political killings and factional battles. There has been some opposition to the encounter from militant groups in <LOCATION> Mamelodi </LOCATION> who say whites should be viewed as enemies. A right-wing white group called <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> sent letters to <ORGANIZATION> Mamelodi </ORGANIZATION>'s mayor and the commissioner of police asking that the meeting be banned. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said some black hosts have expressed fears that they will be arrested if they participate. Most South African blacks know how whites live because they work at white homes and businesses. Few whites know first-hand how blacks live because they seldom venture into the townships located on the periphery of the cities. One of the delegates, <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Prest </PERSON>, said he has had blacks in his house near <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> many times but has never visited a black home. `` The black culture is so set up that they do n't invite people to come,'' said <PERSON> Prest </PERSON>, retired director of a bible study program. `` They'll say, ` Why do n't you just come,' and I'll say, ` I've not been invited.' `` It's just a cultural problem,'' <PERSON> Prest </PERSON> said, `` and also a logistics problem. Also, it's very hard for an African to have you home, because of their accommodation, their facilities.'' The number of black delegates is much lower than the whites, said Baptist Rev. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON>, because it is harder for blacks to take two or three days off work. The main goal, he said, is to expose whites to the black lifestyle, encourage them to think about positive action to change the apartheid system, and take their knowledge back to their communities. `` Maybe for four days we will treat them -LRB- the white visitors -RRB- as blacks. They will start seeing things from the way we look at things, not the way they are used to looking at things,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramakgadi </PERSON>, a field worker for <LOCATION> Koinonia </LOCATION>, one of the organizing church groups.
