<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that foreign investors make `` good corporate citizens'' and should not be discouraged from buying more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets. Despite statistics showing the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> widening its lead as the world's largest debtor nation, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said he had `` very little concern about the issue of direct foreign investment.'' `` We will find that foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be a plus,'' even at present record levels, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> also suggested that a recession is unlikely throughout the next year. He cited recent positive economic statistics, including an unemployment rate that fell to 5.7 percent in February, its lowest level in almost nine years. He said the rate could drop further, probably somewhere between half a percentage point and a full percentage point, before triggering an increase in inflation. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said foreign investments flowing into this country now from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are a direct consequence of the large sums of money the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> spent in those areas in the aftermath of World War II. He testified as the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> current account deficit _ the broadest measure of foreign trade _ surged to a record $ 160.7 billion in 1987. The figures add trade in services and investment flows to other export and import numbers. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said direct investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by foreigners was preferable to them putting their dollars _ amassed through the trade imbalance _ into `` short term liquid holdings.'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> was asked by Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, whether he was troubled by the extent of the growing foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, particularly by Japanese companies. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is buying <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and leasing it back to us,'' <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON> suggested. `` On the contrary, the integration of the world economies ... is inevitable ... and is a desirable trend,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> chief said. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that foreign-owned businesses in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had become `` good corporate citizens in the localities in which they chose to locate.'' He noted that in terms of direct investment _ excluding government securities _ <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business holdings overseas remain about $ 50 billion above holdings by foreigners in this country. In terms of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, foreign investors held 16.4 percent of the total at the end of last year, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> also: _ Urged <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to do more to reduce its trade surplus and bring its economic and monetary polices into equilibrium with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other major trading partners _ Said the British government took the `` correct action'' in not seeking to stem the recent sharp rise of the pound through heavy central-bank intervention _ Praised <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for taking steps to stimulate its economy, but said that steps with a similar goal taken by <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have not been as successful _ Said the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> is keeping in close contact with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on the current turmoil in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> maintains an account for the government of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said.
