<TEXT>
 Bishop <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, named Tuesday as the first black Roman Catholic archbishop in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said his appointment as head of the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> archdiocese is `` a great sign of hope to all our people.'' The appointment by Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> comes more than two years after <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> and other black bishops wrote a pastoral letter calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in official positions. `` The church has spoken but has the church listened to itself?'' said the letter, suggesting that in the absence of a major appointment such as a black archbishop in a big city, `` the church's commitment to black leadership may be seen as half-hearted and superficial.'' The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> archdiocese has only 10,000 blacks among its 156,000 Catholics. Of 52 million Catholics nationwide, 1.3 million are black. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said he could see in his appointment `` a sign of hope to all men and women of good will that the church recognizes its wealth within its own ranks ...'' `` I think that this appointment is a sign of hope to all minorities that the church in general'' and the pope in particular are sensitive to the needs of blacks, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> told reporters. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, 53, is one of 12 black bishops in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and has served as an auxiliary bishop in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, archdiocese since 1974. In 1985, he was elected secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION>, the first black to hold an office in the organization. He is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joseph </ORGANIZATION>, formed in the late 1800s to work in the black community. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>'s selection was hailed by an advocacy group as an outstanding appointment. Calling him `` quiet, but effective,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON>, acting executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholics </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> `` is a pastoral man and he is sensitive to the needs of lay people, especially the needs of black Catholic lay people in the country. `` We have optimism that the church is showing us signs of being responsive to the call by black Catholic lay people for black men to be elevated to positions of authority and responsibilty,'' <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hubbard </PERSON> noted that <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> has represented the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bishops </ORGANIZATION> in congressional hearings, testifying about the needs of the unemployed and the homeless and for voting rights. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said his appointment did not necessarily make him the church's spokesman on civil rights, despite <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s historical position in the civil rights movement. He also declined to be labeled an activist priest, saying he was `` not one to dodge issues; at the same time I am not one to go out and look for issues for issues' sake.'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, said he hoped to be able to expand black membership in the Catholic church. `` We -LRB- black bishops -RRB- feel that this is a good time for our sisters and brothers to come forward with their gifts to enrich the church,'' <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> said. `` We have a rich tradition of spirituality in the African-American tradition ... but it is not a rich tradition that enriches the Catholic church, unfortunately,'' he said. `` Our people tend to be religious, our people tend to be spiritual, but they do not tend to be predominantly <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> and we feel that being <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> is something special.'' After meeting with some of the 200 priests in the archdiocese, <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> led a noontime mass at the Cathedral of Christ the King before returning to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Marino </PERSON> will be formally installed May 5, to succeed Archbishop <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donnellan </PERSON>, who died last Oct. 15. The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> archdiocese covers 69 counties in north <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and has some administrative responsibility for <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> dioceses in the rest of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>.
