<HEAD>Carlucci Meets With Soviet Counterpart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> met with his Soviet counterpart Tuesday, hoping to prod Defense Minister <PERSON> Dmitri </PERSON> <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> into providing concrete evidence of a new Soviet military doctrine. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, speaking to reporters en route to meeting <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION>, said that despite publicity surrounding the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> doctrine of reasonable or defensive sufficiency, he had seen `` absolutely no practical change.'' `` If anything, their military continues to grow. They continue to modernize,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, who also arrived in <LOCATION> Bern </LOCATION> on Tuesday for the opening of the three-day session, said before he left <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> that he hoped for a `` frank, constructive discussion'' on arms control issues including strategic arms, nuclear testing, chemical and conventional weapons. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> emphasized that he did not want the meeting, the first business session between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet defense secretaries, to open a `` parallel channel'' to ongoing superpower arms negotiations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> and <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> were attending a dinner by Swiss Defense Minister <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Koller </PERSON> on Tuesday night, and were to sit down for formal talks on Wednesday and Thursday. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> and other Soviet officials have said they are moving toward a new doctrine, relying on defense. But Kremlin leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, and other military and civilian commentators have offered different versions of the doctrine, puzzling Western analysts. `` I'm still not sure what it is,'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. `` That's a question, by the way, I intend to ask him.'' If <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON> wants to prove that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is moving from an offensive to a defensive posture, said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>, he should seek `` a slacking off in tank production, in artillery production, maybe desisting from highly accurate follow-on systems like the SS-18'' intercontinental ballistic missile, which carries 10 nuclear warheads. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators have raised all those issues in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks, but it is not clear when agreements may be reached to cut strategic and conventional arsenals. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> analysts were looking for unilateral Soviet action to define the new <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> doctrine. `` One of the most important indicators, I would think, would be tanks. But tanks continue to pour out. So there is no indication at the other end of the pipeline that there has been any change,'' said <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON>. <PERSON> Yazov </PERSON>, in remarks reported from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> by the official Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>, said nothing about the doctrine. `` The goal'' of the session, he said, `` is to facilitate the search for ways of resolving the most acute and immediate issues of strategic offensive weapons and the -LRB- 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile -RRB- treaty, reduction of the armed forces and conventional armaments in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, termination of nuclear testing, and prohibition and elimination of chemical weapons.''
