<HEAD>Killer's Surviving Victims Angry Over Execution Delays</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Darden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The two people whose identification and testimony sent <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasper </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> to the electric chair expressed relief Tuesday that their ordeal had ended but anger that it had taken so long. `` I think it's long overdue,'' said <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Turman </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, whose husband, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON>, was shot dead in front of her in 1973. `` I need to get on with my life. ... He -LRB- <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> -RRB- put me through torture. No one knows what I have suffered through his hands. ... It is torture when you see a loved one shot down in front of your eyes.'' A 16-year-old boy who came to her aid in the Turmans' Lakeland furniture store was shot three times but survived. `` Justice has finally prevailed,'' <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said at the <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> asphalt company where he works. `` But it was n't as swift and efficient as it's supposed to be.'' While death penalty opponents and <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> supporters said his execution Tuesday meant the judicial system had failed, the prosecutor, <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON>, criticized the length of the legal battles `` and the unnecessary waste of legal and judicial manpower that went into the case.'' `` Those opponents of the death penalty simply hitched their wagon to the wrong mule,'' said <PERSON> McDaniel </PERSON>, now a private attorney in <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION>. `` I wish 10 percent of their efforts and the money spent could have gone to the victims. ... Mrs. <PERSON> Turman </PERSON>'s life was ruined ... because of this.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, 59, remarried four years ago. She was making breakfast and hurrying to take her husband, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Baum </PERSON>, to a doctor when she was called by a friend and told that <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> had been executed. She cried a little. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Turman </PERSON> rejected recent statements by a Baptist minister and a <LOCATION> Lakeland </LOCATION> secretary, who disputed testimony about the attack. Their statements provided ammunition for <PERSON> Darden </PERSON> and supporters who said he had been wrongly identified as the killer. `` I identified him several days later -LRB- after the crime -RRB- because his face stood out to me. I know in my heart it was him,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Baum </PERSON> said. `` There's no doubt in my mind. There never has been,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>.
