<HEAD>Bill To Be Changed To Avoid Discrimination Against Religious
Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> sponsor of a $ 2.5 billion child care bill said Tuesday he will change it to address complaints that it discriminates against religious groups who provide some of the nation's best child care. `` Within the next week or so we are going to resolve that issue,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., sponsor of the Act for Better Child Care or <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill `` These concerns will be resolved to the satisfaction of all.'' The bill, which has 37 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> co-sponsors, would provide grants to nonprofit agencies to expand child care as well as money for child care certificates to working parents with incomes below a certain level. It would deny funding for `` any program or activity that has the purpose or effect of advancing or promoting a particular religion or religion generally.'' And it would cancel a Civil Rights Act provision allowing religious institutions to hire employees on the basis of religion. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, an official with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, said his group supports the goals of the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill and other child care legislation before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but objects to those two provisions. `` We are working with the sponsors to see if the church-state problems can be resolved,'' <PERSON> Carr </PERSON>, the conference's secretary for social development and world peace, said in an interview. `` Much of the child care now provided is provided in churches and by religious groups, and we do n't want to see an effort to broaden quality child care exclude those groups. We're quite hopeful a solution can be found.'' The <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill was discussed at a hearing Tuesday before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on children, chaired by <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>. Lawmakers across the ideological spectrum are reaching agreement that the nation needs more, better and expanded child care services to address what Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> called `` a bipartisan problem of families.'' The major points of contention are over how much to spend and whether states or the federal government should regulate day care. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, has proposed a somewhat different and less expensive approach to the problem. He said the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill's price tag is prohibitive while its licensing requirements and religious provisions seem to discourage home-based care and participation by religious institutions. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> said the bill's sponsors are `` strong supporters of home care. We just want to see minimum standards'' for day care workers, homes and centers. He said the religious problem would be worked out. The only witness against the bill was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, lawyer representing the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of evangelical Christian educational institutions including 1,000 preschools. <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> said the schools on principle would not take federal money, but said parents otherwise eligible for aid should not be penalized for sending their children there. Conservative activist <PERSON> Phyllis </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlafly </PERSON>, who opposes any federal encouragement of day care, led a