<HEAD>Felde Executed In Louisiana</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Darden Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>, who claimed post-Vietnam War stress drove him to murder a rookie policeman, died in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s electric chair Tuesday after delivering a cryptic two-sentence message to those who watched him die `` You can kill the messenger but you ca n't kill the message,'' he said slowly and matter of factly, giving three reporters separated from him by a glass window time to write down each word. `` Sooner or later, you have to acknowledge it for what it means, not for what you want it to mean.'' The 38-year-old killer was then led by four guards a few steps from the microphone to the big oak electric chair. Four alternating jolts of 2,400 volts and 500 volts of electricity were administered over one minute. Doctors pronounced him deat at 12:14 a.m. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> died for killing Officer <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON> in 1978, as <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> was being driven to jail in <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> had been picked up on a drunkeness charge and apparently had not been throroughly searched. He pulled a gun from his clothes and shot three times through the front seat. Three <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION> officers joined the few pro death penalty demonstrators who come to the remote prison each time the state schedules an execution. `` Justice is being done tonight,'' said Sgt. <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON>. `` I hate it. It took 10 years.'' Cpl. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Feconda </PERSON>, who drove <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON>' widow home from the hospital after the shooting, said he is still haunted by the memory. A third officer declined to be identified. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> was captured the night of <PERSON> Tompkins </PERSON>' murder when a lawman's shotgun blast brought him down Scars from the blast could be seen on the lower right side of his chest as his body was examined in the electric chair. Warden <PERSON> Hilton </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> told reporters shortly before the execution that <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> did not desire or expect a last-minute stay of execution. At his 1980 trial, <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> asked the jury that convicted him to recommend the death penalty, `` or other deaths will result.'' But he later helped in appeals that delayed his execution for eight years. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> had enlisted in the Army at age 18 and was sent to war in 1967. The experience, he claimed, left him unable to tell right from wrong. <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>'s lawyers had hoped Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> _ who took office about 12 hours before the electrocution _ would grant <PERSON> Felde </PERSON> a stay and a new Pardon Board hearing. But <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>, who had said last week he had no plans to delay <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>'s death, decided against stopping the execution after meeting late Monday with <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Quigley </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Felde </PERSON>.
