<HEAD>Brite and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you've been wondering why the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program has fizzled or why <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> ca n't multiply anymore, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Paeltz </PERSON> has an answer: the demise of the slide rule. The headmaster of the Governor French Academy is organizing a National Slide Rule Museum in this southwestern <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> city as a shrine to the device, made virtually extinct by the onslaught of the pocket calculator in the early 1970s. `` The thing that frightens me to death is that we seemed to have gotten along a whole lot better with these than we are getting along with the computer,'' said <PERSON> Paeltz </PERSON>. `` It was the slide rule that put together ` E equals mc squared' and it was the slide rule that put together the beginning of the space program Much of what we talk about as <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s pre-eminent technical position was all computed on slide rules.'' <PERSON> Paeltz </PERSON> yearns for a return to pre-calculator days and thinks many schools put too much emphasis on machines. `` A slide rule is slower, but I wonder if it does n't have some very beneficial things. When there is something physical as well as mental involved in a process I think people remember things better,'' <PERSON> Paeltz </PERSON> said.
