<HEAD>Nation's Urban Schools Failing, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national summit meeting of educators, business leaders and politicians should be convened to combat low morale and high dropout rates in urban schools, the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Teaching said Thursday. `` I see it as a kind of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> Project for urban schools,'' said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON>, referring to the task force of scientists who developed the atomic bomb during World War II. <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON>, speaking at a news conference to release a foundation's report on the nation's big-city schools, said schools must be extricated from `` a web of mindless authority and contradictory responsibilities. `` I wonder if we do n't need a national forum ... of top educators, politicians, corporate leaders, as voices most heard and listened to,'' said <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commissioner of education. The report, the first issued by the foundation trustees, said urban schols were riddled with problems ranging from low morale and high dropout rates to dilapidated facilities and crippling bureaucratic regulations. `` The nation was challenged -LRB- by President <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> -RRB- to reach for the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> within a decade and we did. And I think it's not impossible for us to dream to have inner-city schools of excellence by the year 2000,'' <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> said. In the 38-page report called, `` An Imperiled Generation: Saving Urban Schools,'' the Carnegie trustees said: `` Many people have simply written off city schools as little more than human storehouses to keep young people off th streets.'' <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ikenberry </PERSON>, foundation chairman and president of the Univeristy of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, warned: `` If people in our cities do n't believe that our students can succeed and that our schools can succeed, they wo n't support them and the problem will continue. The foundation called for a `` crusade on behalf of urban education'' including greater financial support for inner-city schools and more freedom and accountability for teachers and principals. Principals and teachers `` should be given more authority to run the schools,'' but if urban schools do not shape up, `` there must be outside intervention,'' the report said. `` It is our deep conviction that when schools fail, swift changes must be made. No other crisis _ a flood, a health epidemic, a garbage strike or even snow removal _ would be as calmly accepted without full-scale emergency intervention,'' the report said. The trustees suggested that an evaluation team of educators, parents and others be dispatched to a troubled school, where it could recommend sweeping changes including removing the principal and, as a last resort, closing the school. `` School reform is failing in the inner city because the diagnosis is wrong,'' <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> said. `` Formulas for renewal _ more homework, more testing, more requirements for graduation _ work best for schools that already are succeeding and for students who are college bound. `` But to require a troubled student in an urban ghetto to take another unit in math or foreign language, without more guidance and support, is like raising a hurdle in the high jump without giving more coaching to someone who has stumbled.'' Secretary of Education <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> issued a statement saying: `` I am generally encouraged by this report. It's good to have major figures from the education establishment strongly endorse the principle of accountability. Now let's see if agreement on this idea can be followed by the political courage required to put it into practice.'' Support for the foundation's effort also came from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the American Federation of Teachers. Carnegie surveyed teachers and visited schools in six cities: <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. It proposed fighting the problem on several fronts, including: _ Setting high expectations for all students It decried the 28 percent of urban teachers surveyed by <PERSON> Carnegie </PERSON> who thought a 25 percent dropout rate was tolerable. _ Freeing principals and teachers `` from a system of red tape that causes them to scrounge for chalk and paper clips while bombarding them with a steady flow of procedural directives. _ A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Schools </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION> that would feature expanded federal funds for Head Start, child nutrition, and the Chapter 1 remedial program, as well as loans to refurbish buildings and other new aid targeted at the nation's 100 biggest cities, from <LOCATION> Worcester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION> -LRB- population 160,000 -RRB- to <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. _ Expanded partnerships between the schools and colleges and corporations
