 Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> on Tuesday disputed reports that riot police clubbed students last week to break up marches commemorating the anniversary of campus protests 20 years ago. He said no general orders were issued for police to use force to stop the March 8 student demonstrations in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. If force was used, it was applied only sporadically when demonstrations turned violent, he added. `` I deny Western reports that police used clubs to disperse demonstrations,'' said Urban at his weekly news conference. `` Police did not have any orders to use force without necessity, without some aggression from the side of illegal demonstrators.'' The demonstrations for more academic freedom coincided with the anniversary of March 1968 student protests against censorship and political repression that were violently broken up by police and pro-government workers. The outlawed Solidarity union condemned the authorities' reaction to the March 8 demonstrations It issued a statement saying that several people were hospitalized after they were beaten by police. The labor group, in a statement drawn up at a meeting Sunday of its <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said the police action reflected `` a growth of repressive tendencies'' on the part of communist authorities. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1983, heads the committee. `` So the situation of 20 years ago has been repeated, which finally puts the lie to the authorities' statements about a change of judgment of the disgraceful events of'68,'' said the statement, which was read over the telephone Tuesday by Solidarity's national spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON>. At Urban's news conference, Western reporters said they had seen riot police charging demonstrators and hitting them with clubs to disperse a march by several hundred students after a Mass at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anne </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. Urban replied, `` You have an undoubted advantage over me ... but it's the task of police to prevent an illegal demonstration.'' The students were demanding restoration of academic freedoms won during the 1980-81 Solidarity labor upheaval and legalization of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, which was outlawed under martial law in 1982. The government said police detained 83 people taking part in the student protests in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION>. Solidarity was chartered by the government during nationwide strikes in the fall of 1980. It was suspended in December 1981 and subsequently outlawed by Parliament.
