<FIRST>r w AM-LeanHotdogs     03-15 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lean Hotdogs,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Processors May Substitute Water For Fat, USDA Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Processors who make hotdogs, bologna and other cooked sausages soon will be allowed to make leaner products by substituting water for fat, so long as there is no loss of nutritional value, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The leaner products can be labeled as `` lite,'' `` light,'' or `` lower fat'' if they contain at least a fourth less fat than similar cooked sausage products on the market, officials said. The labels must include a comparison that explains the term. For example, the label for lower-fat hotdogs might say: `` This product contains 20 percent fat, while <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> allows 30 percent fat in meat hotdogs.'' <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the change in regulations will be effective on April 14 and `` reflects our desire to facilitate the marketing of lower-fat products.'' Current federal rules for cooked sausages limit fat to 30 percent and `` added'' water to 10 percent. The new rule will limit the combination of fat and added water to 40 percent of the product. The maximum fat content in the finished product will continue to be limited to 30 percent, but the water restriction will be removed so that processors can substitute some of the water for fat _ and wind up with a lower-fat product, <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said. Protein content, which is indirectly controlled by the limits on fat and added water, will remain unchanged and will be comparable to other cooked sausages, he said. The rule change is being made at the request of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a private trade association, which asked <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to develop a standard for light frankfurters and similar cooked sausages. The proposed change was announced by the agency on Nov. 25, 1986.
