<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviets Cannot Give Up Central Control</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with later Gorbachev comments, other
details</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> toured a factory Tuesday that exports industrial robots to the Soviets and Americans and told the workers the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is too big to give up all central control. The Yugoslav factory operates under the government's local-management system The reform-minded Soviet leader is on a five-day visit to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, getting his first look at this independent Communist country's freer economy. Soviet officials said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> was `` very satisfied'' with his first two days of talks with <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> leaders and seeks ways of developing closer relations with the country <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> once denounced for `` revisionist'' policies. President <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> broke with Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> in 1948, defying the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s authority in the communist world, and developed ties to the West. Years of plots and threats from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> followed. Relations were mended in the 1950s, with <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> in charge at the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>, but the last visit to <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> by a Soviet leader was in 1980, when <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> attended <PERSON> Tito </PERSON>'s funeral. During a brief photo session Tuesday, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told reporters: `` We got off to a good start.'' The two sides exchanged copies of a new declaration acknowledging <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s independence from Soviet control, which replaces similar statements issued in 1955 and 1956. A Yugoslav spokesman said the document would not be made public until the end of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit Friday. <PERSON> Fyodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON>, a Soviet columnist traveling with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> is preparing to adopt some practices similar to those in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, among them allowing the open sale of international newspapers and magazines. `` Everybody can hear many voices'' in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Burlatsky </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I believe there will be new decisions taken in a short time'' to let <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> newstands sell non-Soviet publications. He also praised progress <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has made `` from bureaucracy to self-managing socialism.'' Public interest remained high in the visit by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Raisa </PERSON>. Crowds gathered to watch the motorcade pass. When word spread Tuesday evening that the Soviet leader would stop in a downtown square, several thousand people turned up, but the stop turned out not to be on his schedule. Earlier in the day, the <PERSON> Gorbachevs </PERSON> visited the Park of Peace to plant a tree, a customary practice. To a group of children attending the ceremony, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the park contains trees planted by many leaders of the non-aligned movement, of which <PERSON> Tito </PERSON> was a founder. `` You take care of this park,'' he said, and carefully shoveled every bit of dirt from a small pile set aside for the planting. After chatting and joking with the children, the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> lined up with them for photographs. He promised the children they would receive copies. At the <PERSON> Ivo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lola </PERSON> <PERSON> Ribar </PERSON> factory outside <LOCATION> Belgrade </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Gorbachevs </ORGANIZATION> were shown modern machine tools and robots used by auto-assembly plants in both the East and West. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> met with the factory <ORGANIZATION> Worker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for plant operations. His `` perestroika'' program, designed to modernize the Soviet economy, proposes reducing central planning and giving managers and workers more control over their own factories, but he told the workers some central control will remain. `` We have to maintain a regulatory role at the center to safeguard us against mistakes, particularly because the country of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is so large,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. He brushed off a reporter's question about what useful knowledge he might take back to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said his schedule was too tight for questions. In a dinner toast, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said `` Eastern and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are gradually becoming less and less suspicious of each other.'' He criticized what he called unfounded charges in the Western media that he is trying `` to drive a wedge'' between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies. `` I have already stated and will repeat once again: We never had, nor do we now have any such ideas,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s largest trading partner. It ships raw materials in exchange for manufactured goods that generally are of higher quality than those made at home. In contrast to perennial Soviet shortages of consumer goods, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s shops and markets brim with domestic and imported products. Inflation is running at about 170 percent, however, the unemployment rate is 15 percent and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> has a $ 20 billion debt to foreign creditors.
