<HEAD>Shultz Says He Hasn't Bridged Differences With Shamir Over Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 6 grafs after 18th graf pvs, The president, with Sen.
Lautenberg quoting Shamir as saying nothing is off the table; picks
up 19th graf pvs, Shultz set</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said Tuesday he was unable to bridge differences with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> over a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan for opening <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION> peace negotiations by May 1. But he called the first of three days of talks with <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> constructive and said `` we feel encouraged to continue our efforts to work with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and others in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> underscored one of the main differences. He said that in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s view, the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace conference <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> wants to convene next month to set the stage for negotiations could not play `` any positive role.'' President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sought, meanwhile, to reassure <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> he would not be put under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure to agree to any particular solution to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 40-year dispute with the Arabs. But <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> stressed that `` making progress toward peace in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> not only serves mutual interests, it is urgent.'' In a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeal </ORGANIZATION>, the president said he would tell <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday that `` peace will not be imposed by us or anyone else.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> for about three hours, first over blueberry pancakes at the secretary's home in suburban <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and then at his <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> office. `` We have n't found our way to bridge all of the differences,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said afterward. `` I see quite clearly what the nature of the differences are and what they are n't.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> did not offer any details, but <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> restated his opposition to an international forum that would include the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which do not have diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and usually support Arab positions. `` We are interested, first of all, to negotiate directly with all the parties concerned,'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said. `` We do n't see any positive role for an international conference.'' The prime minister described his first round with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> as `` very serious and thorough.'' He pledged to cooperate `` to get peace and to enhance the prospects for peace in our area.'' But, he added, the Arabs were not willing to negotiate with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Avi </PERSON> <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal for an international conference was `` a sticking point that has to be resolved if we are going to go ahead.'' King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> has demanded the conference. <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> sees it as `` an instrument which would be used by the enemies of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, both <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> and non-Arabs, like countries that do not have diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, to put pressure on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, to try to bring <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to agree to solutions it would not agree to in free negotiations.'' <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> offered last October to hold Israeli-Jordanian negotiations in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet `` blessing.'' <PERSON> Pazner </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> stands by the offer even though it was rejected by the king. The Israeli spokesman said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> did not give <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> `` an answer'' to the overall proposal for negotiations. `` He did not say yes, he did not say no,'' he said. Speaking a half-mile away, at the Old Executive Office Building next to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said he would tell <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> that `` when it comes to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is not a bargainer or a broker; the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is a friend and an ally.'' The president offered assurances to the Jewish gathering that `` we will not leave <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to stand alone, nor will we acquiesce in any effort to gang up on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' He added: `` Peace will not be imposed by us or by anyone else. It will and must come from the genuine give-and-take of negotiations. That's what we're working to set in motion now.'' In a meeting with a small group of senators at the Capitol, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was quoted as saying he was not ruling out any issue or proposal as the subject for negotiations. `` The prime minister said there is nothing that is off the table in terms of negotiations,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, D-N.J. <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> was asked whether he was ruling out trading territory for peace with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations. `` I did n't hear anything that said territory is excluded,'' <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> said he got the impression that <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> would be prepared to be `` a lot more flexible'' in direct talks with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states than he is in `` this pre-negotiation period.'' But he added: `` I do n't think the prime minister's obstinancy about an international conference is any less than it was earlier.'' He said <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> indicated he might be able to accept `` a ceremonial group'' of other nations at the opening of discussions. `` But once serious discussions started he wanted to talk only to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s -LRB- Arab -RRB- neighbors,'' the senator said. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> set this week as a deadline for a reply from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>, which would form a delegation with Palestinians for the negotiations. In <LOCATION> Amman </LOCATION>, a senior <LOCATION> Jordanian </LOCATION> official told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> was not yet ready to give a final response to <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s plan `` We are consulting with other Arab leaders,'' said the official, who demanded anonymity. Asked when he expected the Jordanian stand to be announced, he said: `` In the next 10 days or so.'' On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> sought to reassure supporters of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> that an international conference would not dictate solutions to any side. `` We wo n't tolerate efforts _ such as ones by the Soviets or the Syrians _ to turn this into an authoritative, plenipotentiary forum,'' he told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Affairs subcommittee <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said the administration still has questions about the terms under which the Soviets could participate in such a forum, and these would be discussed next week when Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> visits <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for talks with <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>. Pressed by several congressmen why <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> had softened his opposition to Soviet participation, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said no Arab state would enter peace talks without a Soviet presence. `` They're -LRB- the Soviets -RRB- in the region, and we have to find a way to deal with them,'' he said. Meanwhile, nine senators made public the text of a letter to <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> urging him not to subject <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> to U. S criticism or pressure. American support should not be used `` as a lever to force <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s leaders to adopt a policy which they see as dangerous to the national security of their country _ especially when such policy entails injecting the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> into the peace process,'' the letter said. The letter was signed by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. Chic Hecht, R-Nev.; <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Symms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>; <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Karnes </PERSON>, R-Neb; <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Colo </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, R-S; and <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, R-Mo. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>'s plan for peace talks anticipates <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> relinquishing at least part of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> it has held since the 1967 Six-Day War in exchange for Arab recognition of the Jewish state. In a tough speech Monday night to another <ORGANIZATION> UJA </ORGANIZATION> group, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> said yielding territory would invite another attempt by the Arabs to destroy <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` These matters are questions of life and death, of our very existence,'' he said. Also on <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s schedule Tuesday were meetings with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, Republican presidential aspirant <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> and congressional leaders.
