<HEAD>Congressman Wants IRS Statement To Taxpayers On National Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> congressman proposed on Tuesday a bill to require the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to send taxpayers a `` credit card statement'' highlighting the cost of federal deficit spending. Rep. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who is a certified public accountant, would require the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> to put the national balance sheet in the format of an individual's regular monthly credit bill. The statement would be mailed with the government's annual income tax forms. `` And I am sorry to report that the bottom line is that the average American owes Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> $ 18,569.10 from all the unpaid bills we have allowed to pile up,'' he said. The national debt is about $ 2.5 trillion. <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>'s sample statement for fiscal 1987 includes the previous balance of $ 17,118.08. It then details the purchases ranging from $ 2,769.34 per taxpayer toward Social Security to $ 73.60 for criminal justice. It then subtracts payments _ taxes _ and adds in the debt's finance charge of $ 1,358,03 per taxpayer <PERSON> Ari </PERSON> <PERSON> Fleischer </PERSON>, a spokesman for <PERSON> DioGuardi </PERSON>, said the congressman had not determined how much producing and mailing the annual statement would add to government spending. But it would be minimized by including it with the other tax forms, he said.
