<HEAD>First Prosecution Witness Takes Stand Against Biaggi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From 1975 on, <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> deceived federal agencies into believing it was a minority-controlled business that qualified for no-bid government contracts, a former company executive testified Tuesday at the racketeering trial of Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, one of four ex-Wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty to bribery and other state and federal charges, was the first prosecution witness to testify at the trial of <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and six co-defendants. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, a 10-term Bronx Democrat; his eldest son; his former law partner; and four others are charged with turning <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> into a racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to win government contracts. Since the allegations became public, the company has filed for protection under bankruptcy laws and suspended most operations. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, who is cooperating with the government in return for leniency, also described <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s lobbying efforts on <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s behalf in 1980 when the company was trying to win an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> contract to build small engines Prosecutors have charged that <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> grew from a small <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> machine shop into a $ 100 million-a-year government contractor, in part, by falsely portraying itself as minority-controlled, in order to qualify for a <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> program that gave out government contracts without competitive bidding. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> said he met <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> co-founders <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuberger </PERSON> in 1976 when he served as consultant for a local program that assisted small minority-owned businesses. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> said the pair later told him that <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON>, who is of Hispanic descent, owned two-thirds of <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, then known as <ORGANIZATION> Welbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Die </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Neuberger </PERSON> owned the other third. <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> is one of those on trial with <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>. <PERSON> Neuberger </PERSON> is one of the four ex-Wedtech officials cooperating with prosecutors after pleading guilty to state and federal charges. In 1979, <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> testified, <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> and <PERSON> Neuberger </PERSON> `` told me they each owned 50 percent of the company'' and that they had a `` handshake agreement'' dating back to 1975. But the pair did not reveal that <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> no longer controlled the company in records presented to the <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> `` in order to comply with the ... regulations,'' <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> said. The witness also said that in 1979, the company had gross revenues of $ 1.5 million and about 60 employees but by the following year `` the company was going bankrupt any minute'' because of a scarcity of funds. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> was in line to get more than $ 4 million in loans through the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in January 1980, but the loan approval was bottlenecked by an overworked EDA official in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` We looked for assistance from several people,'' said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, adding that it came from <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>'s former law partner and current co-defendant, <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrlich </PERSON>, who took <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mariotta </PERSON> to seek the congressman. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> turned the matter over to an aide who knew the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> EDA </ORGANIZATION> official's boss and a month later <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> had the loans approved, said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> also tried to win an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> contract through the minority business program. The contract was for small, gasoline-powered engines even though <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> had neither the experience or facilities to build the engines. When the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> turned down <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>'s first proposal as too high, company officials again went to <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ehrlich </PERSON> for help, said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> enlisted the help of Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and the late Rep. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Addabbo </PERSON>, a powerful <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrat </ORGANIZATION>, who wrote the secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>, which eventually got the contract. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> was scheduled to returned to the stand Wednesday.
