<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The pilot of a Soviet jetliner that crashed killing 11 passengers allowed his co-pilot to try a difficult night landing for which he was not prepared, a government commission said Tuesday. The government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> published the findings of a commission that studied the crash of an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> Tu-154B at the <LOCATION> Caspian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION> on Jan. 18. It said prosecutors have started criminal proceedings in the case. The three-engine jet, carrying 137 passengers from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION> and then on to <LOCATION> Ashkabad </LOCATION> was flying normally until the approach to <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION> in the early morning hours, the report said. Pilot V.S. Churayev permitted co-pilot V.D. <PERSON> Yegorov </PERSON> to land the plan, even though <PERSON> Yegorov </PERSON> was not trained sufficiently for landing in the difficult conditions at <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION>, according to the report. The report did not say why the landing in <LOCATION> Krasnovodsk </LOCATION> was difficult. It said <PERSON> Yegorov </PERSON> made mistakes in his approach that brought the plane down too rapidly from a height of 150 feet and even though <PERSON> Churayev </PERSON> took over the controls at the last minute, the plane flipped over on landing and broke in two. It was one of three times this year that passengers were killed in <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> flight crashes reported by the Soviet media. On Feb. 27 a Tupolev 134 crashed at the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Sumgut </LOCATION>. The media said there were casualties, but did not say how many. On March 8, a family musical group from <LOCATION> Irkutsk </LOCATION> tried to hijack a Tupolev 154 bound for <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. A stewardess, three passengers and five of the hijackers were killed before the pl