<HEAD>Early Federal Strategy Would Have Singled Out Biggest Drug Rings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s criminal division said Tuesday that an early draft of a federal prosecution strategy against drugs would have targeted resources almost exclusively at the world's 150 biggest narcotics rings. Assistant Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> said the approach has been broadened after extensive discussions with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys so that smaller operations will be targeted in federal drug prosecutions. `` I want that dealer in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, not to be sure he wo n't be picked up in a federal undercover operation,'' <PERSON> Weld </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said in an interview `` I do n't want people to be able to relax anywhere.'' <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> said that when he first considered focusing exclusively on the largest drug rings, `` I ran into a little bit of a buzz saw'' from some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorneys. Committing `` an untoward percentage of those resources to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'' and the other major drug centers `` creates the public perception of gaps in enforcement,'' said <PERSON> Weld </PERSON>. `` The bad guys are going to play hit'em where they ai n't.'' `` If we were going to be entirely logical we might say the only purpose of prosecution is to disrupt the supply'' by aiming `` at the top-most levels of supply in the world,'' <PERSON> Weld </PERSON> said. Abandoning regions of the country would send a mixed signal that `` it's not OK to be a member of the <PERSON> Medillin </PERSON> cartel, but it is OK to be a little fish.'' Of the refinements, he said: `` Frankly, I'm happier with the compromise than I was with my own first draft.'' The prosecution strategy is one proposed piece of the federal drug-fighting effort now being mapped out by a number of agencies. The proposals, now in final form, will be presented to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Policy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> for approval and will be publicly announced by early next month.
