<HEAD>GTE Satellite Reaches Geosynchronous Orbit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> communications satellite launched into a low orbit last week rocketed successfully Tuesday into a geosynchronous orbit 22,300 miles above the Earth's equator. The satellite, <PERSON> Spacenet </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, fired its apogee kick motor, a small rocket engine, at 11:57 a.m. EST, some 90 hours after its launch Friday night by a French Ariane rocket. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> officials said the 1,562-pound Spacenet III would initiate a stabilizing spin Tuesday night. This will lock its antennae into contact with <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Once that is accomplished and verified, the satellite will deploy an array of solar power cells that provide the craft with electricity. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> engineers will conduct a series of tests of the craft and the the satellite will start operations early in April. Spacenet III provides a communications link between points in all 50 of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Clients include The Associated Press and the television groups of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> satellite and a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> communications satellite were launched together on Friday aboard an Ariane rocket from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> launch site in <LOCATION> Kourou </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guiana </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spacenet </ORGANIZATION> is the first <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> client of <ORGANIZATION> Arianespace </ORGANIZATION>, the operating arm of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <OR