<HEAD>Federal AIDS Testing May Be Breaking California Law</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lede, INSERTS new 5th graf to reflect that some
routine AIDS tests legal in California.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All blood samples taken for routine clinical testing at 40 hospitals in 30 states now are also being tested for AIDS, the director of <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION>, said at a congressional hearing that `` blinded'' blood tests are being conducted at the hospitals in an effort to help determine the incidence of AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dannemeyer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on health and the environment, asked <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> if he was aware that <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> has a law that forbids AIDS testing without consent `` Then I sure am committing lots of crimes every day,'' said <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>. An official with the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state committee on AIDS such certain `` blinded'' tests are legal. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said the tests were under way in hospitals in both <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> said results of the testing are now being compiled and will be released to the public in two to three weeks. In the `` blinded'' tests, said <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a portion of each routine blood sample taken at the hospitals is separated out and then tested for AIDS. He said the blood used for the AIDS testing carries no identification of the patient who provided the sample, hence the identity of the donor is `` blinded'' to the laboratory conducting the tests. <PERSON> Debra </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, administrative secretary to a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state committee on AIDS, said the `` blinded'' tests are legal. She said a statute passed in 1987 permits such tests for statistical purposes. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s statement came during hearings chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., into the way that the nation's AIDS research dollars are being spent <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, along with Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, and Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyngaarden </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, all said they were experiencing difficulty in hiring scientists and other health care professionals because the federal salaries are below those offered in universities or in industry. <PERSON> Wyngaarden </PERSON> said that the turnover among investigators is about 2 percent a year. `` We're losing some of our most outstanding people,'' he said, for reasons that involved salary, laboratory facilities and other `` complex'' reasons. He said this is particularly true of allied health workers, such as nurses, laboratory technicians and X-ray technicians. He said there is a salary differential among those workers of about 25 percent. `` They will stay through the training period and then leave for more money,'' said <PERSON> Wyngaarden </PERSON>. Dr. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON>, deputy director for AIDS research at <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION>, said top investigators frequently receive offers to move to university or industry positions that offer a higher salary, better facilities and more laboratory personnel. `` There is a rather significant difference in salaries -LRB- between federal and private -RRB-,'' he said. `` We are constantly fighting that battle.'' <PERSON> Fauci </PERSON> said the outpatient clinic at the <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> treated 4,500 AIDs patients during 1987 and that more and more of them are becoming critically ill and in need of intensive care. `` The staff problems will have a negative impact'' on the amount of care available at the clinics, he said. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said his agency is experiencing difficulty in recruiting personnel trained to evaluate drugs and medical issues. He said it typically takes about two years to train personnel, and they often leave the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> shortly after the training is completed in order to receive higher pay elsewhere.
