<HEAD>Butcher, Buser Battle For Lead In Iditarod</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOYUK, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Aiming for a third straight victory as the 1,150-mile Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race neared its end, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON> left this Eskimo village Tuesday with <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Buser </PERSON> just two hours behind her. On the trail to <LOCATION> Koyuk </LOCATION>, Butcher and her 11-dog team overcame a one-hour deficit, passing <PERSON> Buser </PERSON> and building a lead of five hours by the time she reached this village, 171 miles from the finish line in <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>. Butcher rested and fed her weary dogs for more than five hours, leaving at 7:43 a.m. <PERSON> Buser </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Big </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, made up time by cutting his stay in <LOCATION> Koyuk </LOCATION> short. With 12 of his 20 original dogs still in harness, he followed Butcher out at 9:55 a.m. Subzero temperatures and biting winds still hindered the leaders, and forecasters said the wind chill factor could sink to minus 70 degrees along the trail's final miles into <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION>. The winner is expected to cross the finish line at midmorning Wednesday. Butcher, of <LOCATION> Manley </LOCATION>, has won the last two Iditarods, each time proving the strength and endurance of her team in the final, windswept miles along the barren <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> coast. She set a course record with each victory, last year burning up the trail in 11 days, 2 hours. Her closest rival last year was four-time Iditarod champion <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON>, who waged a neck-and-neck race with Butcher until his dogs staged a sit-down strike just 22 miles from the finish. This year, <PERSON> Swenson </PERSON>, of Two Rivers, about six hours behind Butcher at last report, leaving <LOCATION> Koyuk </LOCATION> at 2 p.m. in third place. Running in fourth was <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Garnie </PERSON> of Teller, who arrived in <LOCATION> Koyuk </LOCATION> at 11:49 a.m. <PERSON> Herbie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nayokpuk </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Shishmaref </LOCATION> was fifth. Seventy-year-old <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Redington </PERSON> of Knik, credited with organizing the race but never a winner, was running sixth. He had captured an early-race lead and held onto it for more than 400 miles before falling back. The 16th annual race started March 5 in <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION>. The first musher to <LOCATION> Nome </LOCATION> will collect $ 30,000 of a $ 150,000 purse; the next 19 finishers will split the rest. Finishers have to have at least five dogs in harness at the end of the race in order to qualify. Five of the 52 teams that started the race have dropped out.
