<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 By a wide margin, the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday approved a revised version of a universal health care bill championed by Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to launch the state on an experiment in `` health care for all.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has touted the proposal in his Democratic presidential campaign as a model for the nation. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> endorsed the measure 23-11, sending the bill to a <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> to iron out differences with a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version that would exempt many small businesses and shower favors on certain hospitals. Sen. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> chairwoman and the chief architect of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill, said she was confident a compromise could be worked out swiftly. There are an estimated 600,000 uninsured residents in the state, more than half of them working people whose employers do n't provide health benefits. Among other things, the bill would provide incentives for businesses to offer their own health insurance. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> supporters fought off repeated challenges throughout the day. In a key test, a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> effort to strip the huge health care bill of provisions guaranteeing health care protection to all <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> residents by 1992 was defeated by a 27-9 vote. Senate Minority Leader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who championed the amendment, tried again later, offering an amendment to match the House language and exempt all businesses with nine or fewer employees. That amendment fell short on a vote of 17-19. The exemption, included in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> measure, has been criticized as leaving the entire program open to a challenge on the grounds that it makes the benefits mandatory for some employees and not others. The universal health care proposal has been tied to a bill renewing the state's hospital financing law, providing nearly $ 1 billion in revenue increases for the state's 106 acute-care hospitals over the next four years. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the health care bill two weeks ago, with a maximum price tag for the state of about $ 1 billion over four years to provide insurance coverage for uninsured and incentives to business to offer the benefit to employees. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has estimated the state's cost at about $ 540 million over the same period.
