<HEAD>Unusual Religious Alliance Formed On Middle East Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an explosive time about a tense issue _ <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s dealings with <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> _ a highly unusual American religious alliance has been formed to press for solutions to the crisis. Moslem, Jewish and <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> leaders are included in the new <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interreligious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. What made possible the unlikely combination on the keenly divisive problem was that `` it was an idea whose time had come,'' says <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Young, executive director of the organization. It could n't have happened, he adds, `` unless the time was ripe for it.'' In any case, prominent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Jews and Moslems, who have been on opposing sides in <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> conflict, along with top <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> officials, are extensively involved in the common effort. About 600 religious leaders are initial backers, with other being enlisted, to work for a `` moral climate'' that would spur politicians to take initiatives regarded necessary for <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> peace. Seeking to set forth a middle ground in the conflict, which has particularly divided Jews and Moslems, the committee's joint statement affirms these principles: _ Support of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to secure borders, and also of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> resolution 242 calling for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s withdrawal from the now violence-racked <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> taken in the 1967 war, and security of all states in the region. _ The <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> people's right to self-determination and to choose their own leadership. _ The urgency of an international conference for peace involving all parties in the conflict, as well as members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> security council, including the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been reluctant about taking these positions,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in an interview. `` It has given a higher priority to keeping the Russians out, and this has not been helpful.'' He also said that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration also has not explicitly supported the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION>' right to self-determination, although such a right `` has a history that started in this country.'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said discussions about a joint approach by American Christians, Jews and Moslems started last June, before the outbreak of riots in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, but events there gave the cause increased urgency. They `` dramatically demonstrate that the current situation is disastrous for the <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and, in the long run, will be disastrous for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as well,'' he said. He said local units of the new organization have formed in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION>, <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON>, and are being planned in 11 other cities _ <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C </LOCATION>. He said the aim is to build up a national mood of Jews, Moslems and Christians that would encourage political leaders to act on the problem. `` In dealing with the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, we are dealing not just with the complexities of the particular situation, but with the whole history of prejudice against Jews and also against Arabs and Moslems,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. As a result, he said, `` they have a strong fear against trusting anyone else with the welfare of their people. There also is a great deal of insensitivity among Christians about how deep those fears are.'' The alliance maintains it is urgent that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> make <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> peace a priority of foreign policy. Among backers listed of the new effort: Moslem _ <PERSON> Dawud </PERSON> <PERSON> Assad </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mosques </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Fahd </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Nassar </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, both of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Iman </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deen </PERSON> <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Cherif </PERSON> <PERSON> Sedky </PERSON>, an American-Arab attorney of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> Jewish _ Rabbi <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Schindler </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN