<HEAD>Report: White House Creating New Group For Stock Market Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The White House plans to create a new group that will make final, unified <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration recommendations on how to prevent another stock market collapse, according to a published report. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Tuesday editions that the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, whose <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> task force already has made such recommendations, is creating a new interagency committee to develop a consolidated administration position in the next 60 to 90 days. The committee, which would be headed by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, would include top officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper stated, quoting unidentified White House aides. It was hoped the new committee, details of which still are being worked out, would be able to smooth over conflicts among the various regulatory agencies over how best to prevent another market crash, the newspaper stated. Since the <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> came out with its recommendations in early January, federal regulators have been engaged in often-public sniping over what regulatory changes should be made to prevent a repeat of the Oct. 19 market debacle. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>, for example, has indicated he believed his agency should be chief regulator of stock index futures traded in the commodity markets, a position vehemently opposed by the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> aides suggested that the White House might view such divisiveness as weakening its influence over any legislative response to the October crash. The <ORGANIZATION> Brady </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, headed by former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> senator <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, essentially recommended a coordinated, intermarket system of `` circuit breakers'' to prevent wild price swings; higher margin requirements on stock index futures; unified clearing and settlement operations in the stock and futures markets; and giving the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> superagency authority over key issues affecting the stock and futures markets. The Times said details of the interagency committee were contained in letters sent Friday by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> to White House chief of staff <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, and the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>. In those letters, <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> referred to a conversation with <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> regarding the committee. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> indicated he was pleased with the idea, but also stated that 90 days might be too long for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to wait for the new group's recommendations, given that the agencies involved already had conducted their own studies of the crash and made recommendations. <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> also stated he planned to ask the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> top submit their legislative proposals in time for a March 31 hearing on the issue.
</TEXT>
