<BYLINE>J.P. Stevens In Another Takeover Agreement; Is Bidding Over?</BYLINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Stevens-Glance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Textile industry analysts say the bidding may not be over for <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, even though the company has accepted a nearly $ 1 billion cash buyout offer from an investment group. A group led by <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> announced Monday it agreed to pay $ 61.50 in cash for each of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' 15.5 million shares outstanding, or about $ 953.24 million. The offer is subject to a majority of the shares being tendered and the necessary financing being obtained. Analysts called Odyssey's bid fair, although some said they thought the bidding could continue. In active trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' stock jumped $ 5.37 -LCB- a share to close at $ 61.12 -LCB-. Over the past few weeks, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has fielded rival offers from <ORGANIZATION> Atlanta-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point-Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and a group led by its own senior management, including Chairman <PERSON> Whitney </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, a fifth generation member of the family that founded the company in 1813. The management group offered $ 55 a share in cash and securities in a leveraged buyout about two weeks ago, up from its initial offer of $ 43 a share. In a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely with borrowed money repaid with a target company's profits or the sales of assets. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point-Pepperell </LOCATION>, a major household fabrics maker with brands that include Arrow, <ORGANIZATION> Martex </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepperell </PERSON>, offered to buy <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> for $ 56 a share in cash, or about $ 867 million. The company confirmed Monday it had considered raising its offer to $ 62.50 a share, but had not made a formal bid at the higher price. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point-Pepperell </LOCATION> refused to comment on what, if any, further action it might take. `` The arbitragers think there could be more bidding,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a textile analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Redbook </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Ball </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turben </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` A deal is never done until all the stock is signed over.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmerman </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Gruntal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said a higher offer could torpedo the deal with <PERSON> Odyssey </PERSON>. `` I think they'll have to take the highest bid,'' he said Odyssey is a private investment company. Its deals have included the purchase of a controlling interest in <ORGANIZATION> Lucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eagle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, located in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, and a leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cottrell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a pollution control, engineering and construction company. <PERSON> Odyssey </PERSON> said it would finance the deal with a $ 600 million loan from <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, $ 570 million from the sale subordinated debt and preferred stock and $ 100 million in equity investment. Should the deal go through, <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> predicted, Odyssey likely could sell parts of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> to pay off its debt. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> already undertook a major restructuring about five years ago, selling off some of its finished fabrics divisions to concentrate more on home furnishings. New York-based <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, one of the nation's biggest textile makers with 23,000 employees, produces home fashion textiles such as sheets, towels and carpets under the brand names <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON>. The company also makes automotive products and industrial products. The company had an after-tax profit of $ 56 million on sales of $ 1.6 billion in the fiscal year ended Oct. 31.
