<HEAD>Honda Motor Lacks Punch At Home, But Analysts See Good Potential
For Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Its victories in overseas markets have brought <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> worldwide recognition, but the company still is waging an uphill battle to become a dominant automaker in its own backyard. In sharp contrast with <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s success abroad _ it holds about 3.5 percent of the world auto market _ the company has had trouble penetrating the Japanese market dominated by the `` Big Two'' of <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which together control nearly a 50 percent share. In recent years, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic sales have been growing, often faster than the rate of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s overall motor-vehicle market expansion. To boost growth further, the company will add new cars and models to its product line and increase the number of <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> dealers and salesmen each year into the 1990s, says <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Takashi </PERSON> <PERSON> Kume </PERSON>. By 1991, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> expects its domestic network to grow about 25 percent from now to 3,000 dealers and more than double the number of salesmen to 18,000. New products will allow <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> to sell 800,000 cars and mini-vehicles a year at home by 1991 and 1 million by the mid-1990s, <PERSON> Kume </PERSON> says. These projections compare with last year's sales of 546,979 units and this year's forecast of 620,000 vehicles <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic market share rose to 9.1 percent in 1987 from 7.0 percent in 1986. But in a market where overall demand for cars, trucks and buses, exceeded 6 million units for the first time last year, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> still lags far behind <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>. Analysts say Japanese culture and <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s own history have contributed to its domestic struggle. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> _ originally a motorcycle manufacturer _ had a late start in the auto business, entering the four-wheeled vehicle market in 1963 some 30 years after the Big Two. Analysts say this still haunts the company: <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s sales network of 2,400 dealers and 8,200 salespeople is dwarfed, for example, by <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION>'s 4,000 dealers and 41,000 salespeople. <PERSON> Takamori </PERSON> <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, says <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s `` unspoken dealer loyalty'' is a major obstacle to <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s expansion in the domestic market. `` Unlike the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market, where car retailers are mostly independent -LRB- from manufacturers -RRB- and often switch makers or brands they handle, there is virtually no betrayal on the part of dealers in this country,'' <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> said. Japanese automakers generally maintain high capital participation in their dealers and thus enjoy more control over them. That condition makes a switch, say, from <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, virtually impossible, <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Tetsuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakiya </PERSON>, author of the book `` Honda Motor: the Men, the Management, the Machines'' and professor of international relations at <ORGANIZATION> Musashino </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Womens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, contends <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> could have closed the gap with the Big Two if company founder <PERSON> Shoichiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Honda </PERSON> and his senior officials in the late 1960s had more foresight. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> early on had decided to rely on an air-cooled engine and missed out on the first full-fledged wave of Japanese motorization in the late 1960s and the early 1970s because it did not have the `` right product,'' a car with a quieter and cleaner water-cooled engine, <PERSON> Sakiya </PERSON> said. `` If <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> had n't chosen an air-cooled engine, its standing would've been a lot better against <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> today,'' <PERSON> Sakiya </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> introduced its 1300 model, a sedan powered by an air-cooled engine, in 1969 but replaced it two years later with a lightweight car, the <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Life </ORGANIZATION>, with a much-acclaimed water-cooled CVCC engine. A more conspicuous cause of <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s weakness at home, and in overseas markets to some extent, has been its lack of a full product line and diversity in the styling and size of its cars, according to analysts. Not until October 1985 did <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>, a thriving maker of economical subcompacts, decide to pursue affluent consumers with the Legend, a 2.7 liter-engine luxury car. Because of its relatively limited lineup of models in the over 2 liter engine class, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> will not benefit as much as the Big Two from the boom in the market for bigger, more powerful and more expensive cars, analysts say. To expand its lineup further, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> also recently re-entered the minicar market and is scheduled to launch Japanese sales of a version of the Accord series assembled at its facilities in <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. It is also widely rumored to be planning to introduce a sports car powered by a six-cylinder or eight-cylinder engine next year. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> also is believed to be planning a line of luxury models by the 1990s featuring a flagship sedan with a V-8 or V-12 engine. <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> says to compete domestically <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> also must deal with Japanese upbringing that fosters more conformity and harmony among individuals, compared with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> system that stresses individuality. `` It's easier to sell to Americans who are n't afraid of making their own decisions and accepting the unknown, compared with Japanese consumers who are often oversensitive to impressions they make on others through the purchase of a product,'' <PERSON> Matsuda </PERSON> said. `` The upshot of this -LRB- Japanese -RRB- attitude is that people are driving cars, often white, from the same familiar makers.'' But analysts think <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s potential for sustained growth at home is strong. They concur that <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> is pulling ahead to emerge as the definite winner in a three-way battle for the slot of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s third biggest automaker with <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>.
