<FIRST>r f PM-Polaroid Bjt   03-15 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polaroid, Bjt,0679</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stock Has Jumped Since $5.7 Billion Damage Request In Kodak Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Buoyed by prospects of a billion-dollar court settlement in a 12-year-old patent infringement case and by takeover speculation, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s stock has soared on Wall Street in recent weeks. The instant photography pioneer is seeking $ 5.7 billion in damages from <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which was found guilty in 1985 of violating seven of 150 Polaroid patents when it entered the instant camera business in 1976. After reviewing papers filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here last month, analysts increased their estimates for a possible settlement to above $ 1 billion from their initial $ 300 million to $ 500 million range. `` After reading the documents, a number of people said that <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s case is stronger than we had expected,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The companies are to meet Friday with Judge <PERSON> Rya </PERSON> <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> and may discuss setting a trial date on the damages issue. Analysts said the possibility of a large award has attracted investors and also invited speculation that a corporate raider might bid for the company in hopes of realizing a windfall on a big settlement. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, was trading in the low $ 20s a share until the damage request was disclosed Feb. 19. Since then <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> has climbed, topping $ 36 a share at one point. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> rose 25 cents to $ 34 a share Monday in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. Purchasing patterns have been in small blocks, however, and no individual buyer has notified the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that it holds as much as 5 percent of the stock. Polaroid wo n't comment on stock activity, takeover rumors or a settlement. `` We have indicated from the very beginning 12 years ago that we were always open to an out-of-court settlement,'' spokesman <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` Talking about such matters in the media has a chilling effect on that possibility.'' In court documents, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> argues it is entitled to $ 3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales. The company is seeking $ 2.5 billion more for lost opportunities to develop and market new products. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>, which was ordered out if its $ 200 million a year instant camera business in January 1986, has dismissed the claim as `` ludicrous and ridiculously inflated.'' The <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, N.Y.-based photo giant argues <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> is entitled to a reasonable royalty, not lost profits. If <PERSON> Zobel </PERSON> finds <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> guilty of willfully infringing on <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s patents, pre-tax damages can be tripled under federal law, raising the potential maximum award to $ 11 billion. No one expects the settlement to be that large, but a $ 1 billion award _ equal to about $ 10 a share _ would allow <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> to diversify into fields such as information retrieval or conventional photography. Along with the Polaroid brand name, the possibility that the company could run better under new management is keeping takeover interest high, analysts said. `` It has the characteristics of the type of company that could be run to generate greater cash flow,'' <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Land </PERSON> invented instant photography in 1947 and first marketed it in 1948. Polaroid held a monopoly for almost 30 years until <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> entered the field. Polaroid camera sales peaked at 7.5 million units in 1978 before sinking to 3.4 million in 1984. Sales jumped to 4.4 million in 1986 after the company introduced the Spectra camera, with quality closer to that of 35 millimeter prints, but fell by 16 percent last year. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> had entered the 1970s with high expectations due to technology for its SX-70 camera, which produced fast, dry color prints. But Polaroid never was able to bring the cost of film down enough, which hurt instant photography sales. Analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> could get a boost next month with the introduction of the Spectra 600, priced at $ 40 to $ 60, and the Image, which promises better quality for $ 60 to $ 80.
