<HEAD>Dollar Steadies in Narrow Range; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained against most major currencies in early European trading today. Gold prices were mixed. Dealers said the dollar was trading quietly in a narrow range as market participants awaited Thursday's report of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit for January. The British pound, which soared 10 cents against the dollar in a month, slipped back ahead of the presentation to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> this afternoon of the Conservative government's annual spring budget. Dealers in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> said they were waiting to see whether the budget delivered expected tax cuts and led to lower interest rates. An interest rate cut would rein in the pound. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before it begins in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.02 yen to a closing 127.25. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 127.10 yen. Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's prices, included: 1.6660 West German marks, up from 1.6645; 1.3760 Swiss francs, up from 1.3693; 5.6585 French francs, up from 5.6375; 1.8717 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8645; 1,232.70 Italian lire, up from 1,227.87; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2577 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound was quoted at $ 1.8510, compared with $ 1.8575 Monday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 440.80 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 441.00. At mid-morning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 442.15. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 442.25, up from $ 441.50 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.54 to close at a bid $ 443.27. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.21 a troy ounce, down from Monday's $ 6.22.
