<HEAD>Inventory Growth Slows, Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs on fourth-quarter current account report;
picks up 3rd graf pvs, Analysts said ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The deficit in the broadest measure of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign trade surged 13.7 percent last year to a record $ 160.7 billion, the government reported today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the current account deficit grew from the previous record of $ 141.4 billion in 1986 even though the deficit for the final three months of the year narrowed slightly. The current account covers not only the flow of merchandise across the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> border but also the flow of services, primarily investment earnings between countries. While the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has run deficits in merchandise trade for 16 of the past 17 years, the current account was in surplus as recently as 1981 as Americans' earnings on overseas investments were enough to offset the merchandise deficits. On Monday the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported a 0.4 percent rise in January business inventories, less than half the December increase, reflecting a rebound in car sales that reduced backlogs of unsold vehicles. Analysts said the slower growth suggested the economy may not weaken or lapse into recession in the first half of this year, as had been widely feared following the stock market crash in October. Higher business inventories and sluggish consumer spending are considered a negative trend because they eventually collide to cause production cutbacks and layoffs. The news was ignored by <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, where stocks showed no clear trend in the quietest trading this year. The Dow Jones industrial average gained 15.09 points to 2,050.07, in a session influenced largely by takeover news and speculation. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> totaled 131.89 million shares, the lightest since a 111.58 million-share day on Dec. 29. Prices barely budged in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest rates and the economy. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s closely watched 30-year bond declined -LRB- point, or about $ 1.25 for every $ 1,000 in face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price, edged up to 8.51 percent from 8.50 percent late Friday. Traders were reluctant to buy or sell aggressively, largely because of uncertainty about the January trade deficit numbers to be released by the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. The markets have been fixated on the trade deficit for months because the economy's unprecedented reliance on imports is considered one of the most visible symbols of economic weakness and declining competitiveness. But the deficit narrowed in November and December, suggesting the protracted decline of the dollar over the past two years was helping <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers reclaim foreign and domestic markets from overseas competition.
