<HEAD>ICC Postpones Vote on Merger of Regional Rail Line With Union
Pacific</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 4 grafs new with vote postponed, picking up 2nd pvs,
bgng: The railroads; also moving on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> today postponed a decision on whether to approve a $ 110 million merger that would make the regional <ORGANIZATION> Missouri-Kansas-Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> a part of the giant <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Heather </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON> canceled a scheduled vote, saying that Commissioner <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> had failed to give his fellow commission members adequate time to review his proposed conditions for the merger Under agency rules, commissioners must distribute any amendments the day before a planned vote. <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> did not outline his proposals at today's brief session and, under commission rules, amendments are not made public until they are discussed at a meeting. No new meeting to consider the merger was scheduled immediately, and <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said it was unlikely that another vote will be set before next week. The railroads contend that consolidating operations would provide improved service at lower costs and ensure reliable long-term transportation, especially for Midwestern grain shippers relying on the 3,100-mile MKT system known as the `` Katy.'' Other railroads have questioned whether the proposed merger will reduce competition, because the <PERSON> Katy </PERSON>'s lines generally parallel some <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> routes from <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> to southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and the Gulf Coast. The Union Pacific is a 21,500-mile network formed by a rail merger six years ago. To address those concerns, <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> has offered competing railroads the rights to use some trackage on proposed merger routes. Without the merger, the <ORGANIZATION> ICC </ORGANIZATION> has been told, the financially ailing <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> could face problems surviving against bigger competitors. Operating income for the <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> declined from $ 37 million in 1981 to $ 5 million in 1986. The Union Pacific, the nation's third largest railroad system in terms of track mileage, serves about 20 states with routes from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> in the West to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. The company was formed in 1982 with the merger of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> railroads. The Katy serves six states, with mostly north-south routes running from <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. A separate east-west route extends between <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION>, which filed an application in November 1986 seeking government approval of the <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> acquisition, says the merger would produce operating savings of $ 61 million a year. Company officials say grain shippers would benefit through a shorter, more direct single-line route to export markets in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> ports. However, the merger would eliminate about 1,100 <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> jobs because of closings of rail yards and repair shops. <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> also plans to abandon 405 miles of track, mostly operated by <PERSON> Katy </PERSON>, if the merger is approved. <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> has taken steps to ease objections to the merger. For example, the company has agreed to pay $ 1 million to the southeast <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> community of <LOCATION> Parson </LOCATION> in exchange for not opposing the merger. The city would lose about 300 <PERSON> Katy </PERSON> jobs, with an estimated $ 8 million payroll, under the merger.
