<HEAD>United Artists Communications To Begin Producing Motion Pictures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an entertainment conglomerate with cable television systems and the nation's No. 1 theater chain, has announced the creation of New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Corsair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. The subsidiary firm will develop films that cost between $ 3 million and $ 10 million, an amount considered modest by <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> standards. <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION>, announced Monday that <ORGANIZATION> Corsair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION>'s first production would be `` The Miss Firecracker Contest,'' a comedy written by Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Henley </PERSON>. Actress <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, who was nominated for an Oscar for her role as a newscast producer in `` Broadcast News,'' has been signed to star in the film. <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said the venture was a `` low-key experiment.'' `` We think there is a window for modestly priced, high-demographic films,'' <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. `` We're looking for class. Not art films, but not slash and gash movies either. We're not into teen exploitation films.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, who was nominated for an Oscar as best director for the movie `` <PERSON> David </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>'' has been named to head Corsair. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> had directed for Pyramid Films, also a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION>. Corsair replaces Pyramid Films. <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> expects to produce three or four films a year, he said. `` Frank -LRB- <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> -RRB- has done 17 movies and he's only been over budget once, and that was only be two percent,'' he said. Most of the firm's movies will be for theater distribution, followed by sale to pay television or the video market. Finally they will be sold to cable, he said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> owns 2,000 movie screens, making it the largest chain in the country. `` Certainly having that number of screens gives you a leg up,'' <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> said. `` But a movie has to be released across the board to the most screens for it to generally make sense.''
</TEXT>
