<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed in a very narrow range this morning on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Traders said there was no fresh news overnight to influence the market and little follow-through from Monday's strong performance. Prices were higher across the board on Monday mainly because of a private forcast that farmers will be planting fewer acres of soybeans this season than had previously been thought. The estimate pegged soybean acreage at 57.5 million acres, only slightly higher than the 57.4 million acres planted last year. On the opening, wheat was unchanged to -LCB- cent lower with the contract for delivery in July at $ 3.07 a bushel; corn was unchanged to \ cent higher with March at $ 1.98 -LCB- a bushel; oats were unchanged to -LCB- cent higher with March at $ 1.90 \ a bushel; and soybeans were -LCB- cent lower to -RCB- cent higher with March at $ 6.14 \ a Livestock and meat futures were mostly weaker on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .15 cent higher with the April contract at 73.70 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .33 cent higher with March at 82.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to .10 cent higher with April at 45.15 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .17 cent to .42 cent lower with March 53.40 cents a pound. On Monday, livestock and meat futures were higher across the board.
