<HEAD>New Jersey Company Makes Spray Cans For Ketchup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Imagine spraying ketchup on a hamburger or spritzing mustard on a hotdog with an aerosol-like can. A Hoboken-based company wants just such containers to become commonplace in kitchens across <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Enviro-Spray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> also hopes its packaging technology, already popular in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, will help transform the 8-year-old research and development company into a profitable manufacturing and marketing firm. The company, which went public last year, hopes to have lines of sprayable ketchup, tomato sauces and mustard in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stores by June. Mayonnaise, chocolate and apple sauce are waiting in the wings, said company President <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON>. `` It's the beginning of something very, very important,'' he said in a recent interview. The patented spray process was introduced successfully in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where it is used to dispense a popular form of shave gel as well as condiments, hand cleaners and pharmaceuticals. For its push into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Enviro-Spray will focus on food products, said <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, assistant to the president. And for the first time, the company will get involved in selling the products as well as the process. The ketchup, mustard and tomato sauce to be marketed here is made by the French concern CCRF under the <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Vetillard </PERSON> label, Ms. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said. Essentially, the cans resemble aerosol sprayers but do not mix other substances with the product to be dispensed. Inside the can is a pouch with sodium bicarbonate and citric acid, which is activated by a button on the can. When the can is activated, the two chemicals react inside the pouch, creating pressure that forces the product out. And presto, a thin stripe of ketchup is applied to your waiting hot dog. The `` GrowPak'' pouches are tamper proof and the food needs no refrigeration, has a longer shelf life and is more convenient to dispense, <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> said. Since no propellants are needed to make the cans work, no fluorocarbons, identified as harmful to the protective ozone layer in the atmosphere, are introduced into the environment. Banks said he hopes such advantages will convince consumers and restaurants to buy GrowPak products and help make the company profitable. Enviro-Spray had a net loss of $ 448,000 on sales of $ 455,000 in the second quarter ended Dec. 31. That compared with a $ 1 million loss on sales of $ 191,000 in the same period a year earlier. Ms. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> attributed the losses to the heavy start-up costs associated with the development of the equipment that manufactures the pouches. Banks sees the company entering the black by 1989. `` When people get their hands on these cans, they really love -LRB- them, -RRB-'' he said. Whether they will be willing to spend two to three times more for them _ $ 2.50 to $ 3 for a 9-ounce can, as Banks described their cost _ is another question. `` I doubt people would be willing to pay that price,'' said <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, Pa.-based H.J. <ORGANIZATION> Heinz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a leading <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ketchup producer. Ms. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> said she had never heard of the process. `` It just seems like a strange idea,'' she said, adding that consumers may have a difficult time accepting a food product in a type of container that usually dispenses hairspray, carpet cleaner or disinfectant. About 30 percent to 40 percent of the ketchup market is contained in plastic squirt bottles, a development of only the last decade, she said. Enviro-Spray also sells its system to drug, cosmetic, pet and plant care companies, <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> said. Last year, 10 million pouches with the system were sold in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and 15 million are expected to be sold this year. Banks hopes to sell 10 million in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1988. Company officials believe their business will grow as the products in the cans catch on. `` The more cans of <PERSON> Vetillard </PERSON>'s ketchup we sell, the more pouches we sell to them,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Black </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 19-20</NOTE>
