<HEAD>FEMA Withdraws Key Objection To N.H. Evac Plans For Seabrook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Emergency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has withdrawn a key objection to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>'s emergency evacuation plans for the $ 5.3 billion <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> opponents, citing the removal of a key critic of the plans from a <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> review board, charged that the agency caved in to pressure from the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the plant's owners A <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> spokesman today called that charge `` a smokescreen.'' A <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman would not comment. The agency said in testimony to the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Monday that shelters are not needed and evacuation alone offers enough protection for people that crowd beaches near the seacoast reactor on hot summer days. Last summer, the agency would not approve the plans, citing 55 deficiencies observed in a February 1986 drill. A major objection was that there are n't enough airtight buildings to protect people from dangerous radiation that could be released in an accident. Now the state has considered sheltering and determined that `` in most cases evacuation would be a preferred option and would provide ample time to move the beach population from the area safely, before there would be any radioactive release,'' <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Scanzoni </PERSON> said today. <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION>'s new testimony concludes: `` The requirement for a range of protective measures has been satisfied, even though the state of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> has chosen not to shelter the summer beach population except in very limited circumstances. With respect to the summer beach population, -LRB- federal standards -RRB- have been met.'' <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> officials acknowledged in their testimony that they were deferring to the <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff's argument that evacuation offers better protection than sheltering. The <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> staff and other four other federal agencies out of eight involved in an interagency review of the plan had been trying to persuade <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> to change its position, according to testimony during hearings on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> plans. The other four were the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> is completed but unlicensed until it can gain <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> approval for evacuation plans for a 10-mile zone around it. An <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> licensing board resumes hearings next month on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> plans. <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> officials wo n't cooperate in planning for six <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities within the 10-mile zone. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> has submitted its own plans for <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. No hearings have been set. The new <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> testimony stopped short of endorsing the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> plans, but it clears a major obstacle. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Backus </PERSON>, lawyer for the <ORGANIZATION> Seacoast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anti-Pollution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I view it as a total agency collapse.'' He noted that <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, a top <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> official in its Northeast regional office who had written the earlier criticism of <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s plans, was not involved in the new testimony. `` I suspect that there was a fight for the soul of the agency here and the guys who are no longer the witnesses are not the guys who won the fight,'' <PERSON> Backus </PERSON> said. `` <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> has capitulated to those who want <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> licensed regardless of the fact that minimum safety requirements can not be met,'' said <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> McAda </PERSON> today declined to comment on the new testimony and on charges that the agency succombed to pressure to change its opinion. <PERSON> Scanzoni </PERSON> denied that <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> officials pressured <ORGANIZATION> FEMA </ORGANIZATION>.
