<HEAD>Parliamentary Uproar Over Tax Cut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> announced <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s first budget surplus in nearly 20 years today and was shouted down by opposition legislators in one of the unruliest annual budget presentations in parliamentary history The deputy speaker twice suspended the proceedings during <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s speech, and opposition socialist Laborites chanted `` Shame, Shame'' as he announced huge tax cuts for the rich. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said he was slashing the top tax bracket from 60 percent to 40 percent. A Scottish legislator, <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Salmond </PERSON>, was expelled after calling the budget an `` obscenity,'' with tax cuts instead of extra spending on health and welfare services. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s speech was halted while legislators voted overwhelmingly to expel <PERSON> Salmond </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> reduced the basic rate of tax from 27 percent to 25 percent, and cut <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s six tax brackets to just two _ 25 percent and 40 percent. The 40 percent top tax rate _ down from a 60 percent top bracket _ will be payable on income over 19,300 pounds -LRB- $ 35,700 -RRB- a year. The measures were the most sweeping changes since Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> came to power on a platform of cutting taxes, encouraging private enterprise and curbing inflation and state spending. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> announced last autumn the size of the $ 290 billion budget for the fiscal year ending in 1989. Today, armed with the battered leather budget box, the chancellor disclosed how the government will raise the money. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, declaring Conservative government has transformed the British economy, announced a surplus of 3 billion pounds -LRB- $ 5.5 billion -RRB- in the budget. `` Tax breaks for the rich, poll tax -LRB- a new property tax -RRB- for the poor and nothing in it for the health service _ it's an absolute and utter obscenity,''' shouted <PERSON> Salmond </PERSON>, of the Scottish <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. His expulsion went ahead after a vote that delayed <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s speech for 12 minutes The two other Scottish nationalists in the 650-member Commons walked out in sympathy. As the session resumed, Laborites murmured restively as <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> continued to list tax cuts. The opposition broke into a new uproar, amid shouts of `` rich man's budget.'' Conservative legislators, opposite the Laborites from the facing green leather benches, yelled `` Quiet'' and `` Sit Down.'' The proceedings then were suspended a second time. Parliamentary officials hustled four uniformed nurses out of the public gallery after they shouted slogans in defense of state-funded health care. `` The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is not safe in your hands. Thanks a lot <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>,'' one shouted. Despite buoyant revenues and economic growth, today's budget was clouded by a split between Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> on how to handle the soaring British pound. Even with eve-of-budget hesitancy in currency markets, the pound finished at $ 1.85 on Monday, up 8 cents in a week, and at 3.08 West German marks, well above the 3-mark level central to <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s strategy of keeping a rein on sterling A high pound hurts British exports. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> last week ruled out such intervention as immediate pound sales by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> and lower interest rates to depress sterling on the grounds that the moves would fuel inflation. A budget focusing on tax reform rather than huge giveaways would likely be another boost for the pound. The budget surplus is due partly to higher-than-anticipated revenues from increased wages and company profits. In line with a string of trim, low deficit budgets since Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> won power in 1979, <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> originally predicted a $ 7.4 billion deficit in 1988-89, and revised that to $ 1.85 billion last autumn.
