<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment partnership has filed a class action lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, alleging it was responsible for millions of dollars of losses during the October market crash. The lawsuit, filed Friday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, also names the <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clearing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which processes all securities options trades in the nation. The investment partnership, M & amp; M, sued on behalf of the more than 1,000 customers it said traded in excess of $ 40 million worth of a November series of stock options on the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 100 stock index. The investors contend the exchange violated its rules by not halting trade in stock index options in a more timely fashion. It said the exchange operated a `` fraud and deceit upon the plaintiffs'' by failing to maintain a fair and equitable market. Exchange spokesman <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Moulds </PERSON> said it `` wo n't comment on pending litigation.'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hender </PERSON>, executive vice president of the clearing corporation, said he could n't comment because he had not seen the lawsuit. The lawsuit contends that on the morning of Oct. 20, the day after the crash, <ORGANIZATION> M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M put in an order to buy November put options. A put option gives the buyer the right to sell stock index contracts at a set price before the expiration date. The system in use at the exchange requires that opening trades be rotated among the various contracts, and that free trading begins only when the rotation is completed, the lawsuit said. The average length of the opening rotation is 12 to 15 minutes, it said, but in the hectic aftermath of Black Monday, opening rotation took 2 hours and 30 minutes. By the time M & amp; M's contracts were executed, prices `` were arbitrarily high and grossly inflated,'' the lawsuit contends. `` Once they placed that order, they could n't withdraw it,'' said attorney <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lasky </PERSON>, who represents <ORGANIZATION> M </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; M. `` They were locked in.'' The lawsuit contends that for the investors to have broken even, the Dow Jones Industrial Average would have had to plunge an additional 50 percent by Nov. 20, the expiration date of the options. M & amp; M invested $ 23,400 and lost 90 percent of it, <PERSON> Lasky </PERSON> said Tuesday. The class of investors, which had put up more than $ 40 million, probably lost close to 90 percent, too, he said. The lawsuit asks that the investors be reimbursed.
