<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Budget 1stLd-Writethru f0193 03-15 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0193,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Unveils Sweeping Tax Reform, and Rare Budget Surplus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead graf. SUBS 6th graf pvs, Lawson said ... to
CORRECT typo. Pick up 7th graf pvs, Tax rates ...; also ran on
general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Conservative government unveiled on Tuesday a sweeping reform of the British tax system, slashing rates for higher income groups in a move that provoked an uproar from the parliamentary opposition. Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s government also announced a $ 5.55 billion budget surplus, the country's first in almost 20 years. `` Shame, shame!'' and `` Rich man's budget!'' opposition members shouted as Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> presented the annual spring budget statement to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>. A Scottish legislator, <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Salmond </PERSON>, was expelled after he called the budget an `` obscenity'' with tax cuts instead of extra spending on health and welfare services. The budget served notice that in her third consecutive term as prime minister, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s faith in her 9-year-old capitalist revolution is undimmed, and that the socialist opposition can expect few concessions. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said the government would abolish four income tax brackets, leaving just two, of 25 percent and 40 percent, in the fiscal year beginning April 1. Tax rates currently range from 27 percent to 60 percent. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s statement was repeatedly disrupted by opposition lawmakers, especially when he announced a huge tax cut to 40 percent for top earners. `` Tax breaks for the rich, poll tax -LRB- a new property tax -RRB- for the poor and nothing in it for the health service _ it's an absolute and utter obscenity!'' shouted <PERSON> Salmond </PERSON>, of the Scottish <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. A few minutes later, the deputy speaker of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> was forced to suspend proceedings as shouting continued. Four uniformed nurses were ousted from the public gallery for yelling at <LOCATION> Lawson </LOCATION>. Custom dictates a respectful hearing of budget statements, but <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinnock </PERSON> described <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>'s budget as a `` tragedy.'' `` This is puny, marginal and negligible for the average people in our society,'' he said. He claimed the surplus came from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> oil sales, taxes on a `` massive expansion'' of household credit debt, and `` the once-and-for-all sell-off of national assets'' _ a reference to the sale of state-owned industries to the private sector. But <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> said: `` This major reform will leave us with one of the simplest systems of income tax in the world.'' The proposed tax changes are part of Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s long-term overhaul of the tax system and resemble recent reforms in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s goals have been to reduce and simplify taxes and transfer the tax burden from income to spending. Financial markets were buoyed by the statement with the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index closing up 20.4 points at 1,839.9. The pound moved hiher, but its advance was checkedby reported intervention by the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>, dealers said. The spring Budget Day is when the government announces how it will raise its revenue. The government last autumn announced its planned expenditures of $ 290 billion for the fiscal year ending March 31, 1989. The budget proposals must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Tories </ORGANIZATION>' 102-seat majority in the 650-seat <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> guarantees their passage. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> that the public service borrowing requirement, the most commonly used measure of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s budget deficit, would be in surplus of $ 5.55 billion in the year ending March 31, when the government spent $ 273 billion. It was only the second surplus since the early 1950s. The last, in 1968-69, was about $ 1.1 billion. The government most recently had forecast a deficit for the current year of $ 1.85 billion, down from an original forecast of $ 7.4 billion. <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> also said he plans for a similar surplus in the new fiscal year. `` Having achieved it, I intend to stick to it,'' he said. The focus of the statement was on tax reform, however, with <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> saying he planned ultimately to lower the 25-percent tax rate to 20 percent. Under the new system, the higher 40 percent rate will apply to income above $ 35,705. Currently the 27-percent rate applies to income up to $ 33,115, and the top rate of 60 percent is on income above $ 76,220. In her first budget, in June 1979, Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> cut the top rate from 83 percent to 60 percent. The lowest rate stood at 33 percent in 1979.
</TEXT>
