<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar gained against most major currencies Tuesday in reaction to weakness in the British pound. Gold prices also rose. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 446 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $ 441.90 an ounce late Monday. The British pound rose sharply during a budget announcement by Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON>, who announced <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s first budget surplus in nearly 20 years and a sweeping tax reform Later, though, the pound fell back as investors cashed in on paper profits and word that the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> was selling sterling to stem its rise. As sterling fell, the dollar benefited, said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Conte </PERSON>, vice president for foreign exchange in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. Gold and silver strengthened in a speculative run-up. Traders said the peg for gold's rise was word of increased tension between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. In late <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading, the British pound was quoted at $ 1.8570, down from $ 1.8575 Monday. Later, in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound was quoted at $ 1.8455, down from $ 1.8540. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before it begins in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.02 yen to a closing 127.25. Later in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 127.10 yen. At the end of the trading day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar rose to 127.38 yen from 126.78 late Monday. Other dollar rates late Tuesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday, included: 1.6699 West German marks, up from 1.6629; 1.3805 Swiss francs, up from 1.3718; 1.2539 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2572; 5.6660 French francs, up from 5.6395; and 1,237.00 Italian lire, up from 1,231.25. Other dollar rates late Tuesday in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday, included: 1.6650 West German marks, up from 1.6645; 1.3760 Swiss francs, up from 1.3693; 5.6605 French francs, up from 5.6375; 1.8705 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8645; 1,232.40 Italian lire, up from 1,227.87; and 1.2564 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2577. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 443.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 441.00. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the late bid price was $ 442.50, up from $ 441.50 late Monday. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery was bid at $ 446.30, up from $ 441.90 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.54 to close at a bid of $ 443.27 an ounce. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Tuesday at a bid price of $ 6.25 a troy ounce, up from Monday's $ 6.22. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was bid at $ 6.365 an ounce, up from $ 6.24 late Monday.
