<HEAD>Domestic Car and Truck Sales Up 6.3 Percent in Early March From
1987</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix numbering sequence.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Led by a generous jump in purchases of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vehicles, sales of domestic cars and light trucks rose 6.3 percent in early March from a year ago, automakers reported Tuesday. Industry-leader <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, however, did not share the strong sales increases enjoyed by No. 2 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and incentive-heavy <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> `` I'm surprised how strong sales were considering that some consumers had moved their -LRB- March -RRB- purchases into February in expectation of sales incentives expiring,'' said industry analyst <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s combined domestic car and light truck sales were the highest for early March since 1979, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic car sales jumped 21.4 percent to 68,859 in early March from 50,407 a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> held 32.5 percent of the domestic car market, up from 27.7 percent a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s light truck sales rose 18.1 percent to 46,073 in early March from 34,685 a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s share of that market improved to 39.5 percent from 37.4 percent a year ago. Despite its incentives, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic car sales fell 13 percent from early March a year ago and its light truck sales dropped 1.5 percent, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> and other analysts blamed the end-of-February expiration date of most of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s incentive programs for its strong February showing and ensuing weakness in early March. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> later extended the buyer lures into the spring, but only after many consumers had hurried to take advantage of the discounts before they ended. At the same time, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sweetened its incentives in early March, helping its sales. The eight companies that build cars and trucks in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> sold 328,437 in the nine selling days from March 1-10, up from 274,626 in eight days a year ago. Sales have improved in each of the seven sales period so far in 1988 compared with the first quarter of 1987, when showrooms were empty because buyers made their pre-tax reform purchases at the end of 1986. The percentage that sales fell or increased is a comparison of average daily sales during the period, not of the straight numbers of vehicles sold in early March this year and last year. Automakers sold 211,772 domestic cars in early March, up 3.5 percent from 181,820 a year ago, and 116,665 light trucks, up 11.7 percent from 92,806 a year ago. Despite the addition of new mid-size models, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic car sales fell to 95,372 from 97,487 a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s light truck sales fell slightly to 42,489, or 4,721 a day, from 38,327, or 4,790 a day, in early March 1987. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the domestic car market fell nearly 9 percentage points in early March to 45 percent from 53.6 percent a year ago. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> lost nearly 5 points of share in the light truck market at 36.4 percent, down from 41.3 percent ago year ago. Sales of Chrysler domestic cars rose 18.3 percent to 34,667 from 26,046 a year ago. Sales of Chrysler domestic light trucks jumped 24.1 percent to 25,287 from 18,108 a year ago. The No. 3 automaker held 16.4 percent of the domestic car market, up from 14.3 percent a year ago, and 21.7 percent of the light truck market, up from 19.5 percent a year ago. Together, the Big Three held 93.9 percent of the domestic car market, down from 95.7 percent a year ago, and 97.6 percent of the light truck market, down from 98.2 percent in early March 1987. Among the remaining companies, leader <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 71.9 percent jump in sales of cars built at its <LOCATION> Marysville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, factory. <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> domestic car sales rose 97.3 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> domestic car sales fell 19.7 percent from a year ago but its domestic truck sales rose 48.5 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s domestic car sales dropped 18.6 percent.
